SOC 250-001 
21 September 2025 
The Community Consideration 
Answering the question of “What’s the right thing to do?” has been a focal challenge for philosophers across centuries, remaining unanswered even by the prolific Harvard professor, Michael J. Sandel, in his book titled “Justice.” To better address the broad topic of justice, Sandel identifies three approaches to the concept: welfare, freedom, and virtue. He concedes at the end of his book that he ultimately favors the approach of virtue and the common good. Ultimately, Sandel advocates for a theory that aligns with communitarian ideals, challenging the notions of the philosophers he writes about. As he approaches his conclusion, Sandel takes his readers on a journey through the theories of Bentham, Kant, and Rawls to question which theory addresses fairness and justice most effectively. 
Sandel refers to the teachings of Jeremy Bentham as he discusses and critiques the theory of utilitarianism. Concerning his theory and justice, Bentham argues that “the right thing to do is whatever will maximize utility” (Sandel 34). Simply put, people are obligated to make decisions that maximize happiness and minimize pain. The straightforward nature of the theory gave rise to objections, which later utilitarian philosophers like J.S. Mills would attempt to remedy. However, Sandel still finds conflict with the fundamental theories that underlie utilitarian thought. 
Sandel’s first critique argues that utilitarianism diminishes individual rights by weighing the heightened pleasure of a majority over the pain of a few. He cites the example the city of happiness, in which one child is condemned to a life of suffering so that the rest of the city can flourish. Sandel says that although the majority benefit, it is still wrong to violate the child’s rights. Sandel’s second critique focuses on the issue of utilitarian calculus and the uniform value measurement the theory requires. To calculate the offset between pleasure and pain, a value may be attached to human life. In times when anti-smoking movements or even car brands have attempted to define the value of a human life to conduct utilitarian calculus, the public has lashed back. The sentiment of the public is shared with Sandel—attempting to attach value to something as abstract of human life ultimately diminishes it. 
Sandel’s alignment with communitarian thought strongly contrasts utilitarian philosophy. A communitarian perspective would argue that as utilitarianism weighs the value of each person equally, communal ties people may share with family members or fellow citizens are disregarded. Take for example the famous trolley problem. If one track contained two strangers and the other contained someone’s child, the utilitarian would argue that saving the two strangers would likely override any loyalty to family, as the net happiness of saving two strangers outweighs saving one. Examining this problem through a utilitarian perspective devalues the relationships people have between each other. Sandel also highlights how communitarian thought clashes with the basic utilitarian tenet of maximizing happiness through his discussion of patriotism. Not only are familial ties at odds with utilitarian thought, so too are ties between citizens and their country. For example, a utilitarian could also find issues in the “Buy American” movement. In response to decreasing industrial prowess in America, congress passed a stimulus bill that was aimed at reinvigorating American industry. Through a utilitarian lens, one could argue that happiness and pleasure could have been maximized by injecting that money into a struggling, developing nation that needed it more than a still relatively robust American job market. However, communitarian principles would include the influence of people’s obligation to the communities they are a part of, and the bonds shared between countrymen. 
Sandel further explores his theory as he examines the theories of Emmanuel Kant and John Rawls. Both philosophers advocate for a neutral view of justice but arrive at that conclusion through different methods. Kant’s theory breaks away from the utilitarian principle of maximizing pleasure through its introduction of two categorical imperatives, the first of which refers to adhering to universally applicable principles, and the second arguing that people must always be treated as ends in themselves. The two categorical imperatives define Kant’s moral law through its emphasis on autonomy. Freedom and autonomy are derived from acting on reason, separating oneself from desires and instead acting according to universally willed maxims. Treating people as ends, rather than means, leads to ultimately respecting everyone as a rational being that has the capacity for self-direction. This view abstracts individuals from a society that offers competing visions of the good life, allowing people to define their own moral code. 
Rawl’s theory also reaches a neutral view of justice through the concept of “the veil of ignorance.” To develop a fair and equal society, the principles that govern said society should be made behind this veil, which strips individuals of knowledge about their social position, class, natural talents, gender, religion, and other factors that could result in biased thought. Rawls’s idea of autonomy derives from the idea that individuals choose principles of justice through rational deliberation, rather than making decisions under the influence of interests or attachments. A lack of preconception of what the good life is results in a neutral conception of justice in Rawls’s theory. 
Sandel’s alignment with communitarian thought leads him to conflict with Kant and Rawlsian theory. The first conflict arises as Sandel introduces the obligation of solidarity. Kant’s belief in the abstraction of self and Rawls’s concept of the veil of ignorance are essential in their respective theories to maintain their neutral attitude towards justice. However, these beliefs discredit the important influence of people’s communities and traditions. Kant and Rawls ignore this influence through their belief that obligations are either natural, derived from the social contract, or are voluntary, based on explicit consent. 
Sandel’s reference to the obligation of solidarity highlights the importance of the bonds formed through family ties, shared history, or citizenship. Sandel references two examples in his discussion of familial obligation. The first follows a parent choosing to save their child first out of two drowning kids in a river. The second example reverses the roles, referencing a child choosing to care for their sick mother first over caring for someone else’s sick mother. In either of these cases, Kant and Rawls would attempt to derive the obligation to one’s family by tracing it back to consent or some universally recognized duty. However, Sandel argues that these obligations are derived from the shared history and relationships between family members. 
Attempting to separate familial, or communal ties, from the notion of obligation showcases Kant and Rawls’s continued fealty to their broader views on neutrality. Kant’s abstraction of the self and Rawls’s insistence on the separation of aims, attachments, and conceptions of the good are evidence of their attempts to safeguard autonomy by keeping justice impartial. Sandel, however, drawing on Aristotle, argues that conversations about justice cannot be neutral. The development of a just constitution not only distributes rights but is necessary to “form good citizens and to cultivate good character” (Sandel 242). Aristotle’s theory directly conflicts with Kant and Rawls’s championship of individual freedom by attempting to cultivate and instill certain values. The two philosophers address moral influence on government by advocating for a neutral moral framework. Rawls even concedes that people may be burdened by their own loyalties but argues that these attachments should have no influence on one’s identity as a citizen and be removed from debates about justice and rights. 
In contrast, Sandel argues that justice demands the influence of personal attachments and morality. In fact, he even goes so far as to say that neutrality in government is impossible. He mentions debates over abortion. In a pro-choice versus pro-life debate, it's easy to fall into the trap of believing that government neutrality would agree with a pro-choice argument. However, as Sandel points out, even choosing to remain “neutral” makes a moral claim, which would be that the contesting belief that life begins at conception is wrong. Similarly, in discussing the legality of gay marriage, Sandel points out that government cannot remain neutral about the definition of marriage. Either marriage is defined as a moral good, open to all relationships, or it is restricted based on contesting moral definitions. As the only true way to ensure freedom in the case of marriage would be to outsource the burden to private associations, it is impossible for the state to remain morally neutral. Through these two concepts, Sandel illustrates how pluralist societies inevitably face moral conflicts that must require moral judgement. While Kant and Rawls defend neutrality to protect the right of individuals to pursue their own good, Sandel insists that community ties and moral purposes are inescapable in political life. As he closes out his novel, Sandel says that “a politics of moral engagement is not only a more inspiring ideal than a politics of avoidance. It is also a more promising basis for a just society” (Sandel 269). Justice cannot remain neutral but rather must involve a collective process of reasoning about the good, a necessity that communitarianism addresses. 
Sandel’s novel “Justice: What’s the Right Thing to Do?” navigates several compelling theories that attempt to answer that very question. However, Sandel provides a potent critique of the philosophy he references, namely Bentham’s utilitarianism, and Kant and Rawls’s individualism. He concludes that communitarianism and the obligation of solidarity answer questions that former theorists cannot and ultimately lay the foundation for the development of a more just and united society. 


Work Cited 
Sandel, Michael J. “Justice: What’s the Right Thing to Do?” Farrar, Straus, and Giroux, 2009.

22 October 2025
The Future of Family
Since the beginning of the 1950s, and especially in the 1970s-80s, the United States has seen drastic changes in the structuring and defining of an “average” American family. This can be attributed to many factors, including the rise of women in the workforce, the culture wars in the 1970s/80s, legalization of interracial and same-sex families, etc. During the culture wars, the country was split between traditional family ideologies and progressive, modern family ideologies, which respected the idea that there are multiple types of families (Coontz, 2015). Since that point, the United States has seen an increase in divorce rates, cohabitation, age of first marriage, single parenting, etc., and on the other hand has seen a decline in marriage rates and fertility rates. Gender roles in the family have become more equitable with the entrance of women in the workforce, the feminist movement, and the increase of dual-income households but in general, women today still take on the majority of the childcare and housework (Percheski, 2013). The “traditional” nuclear family model has become increasingly less popular over the years, until recently with the resurgence and growing popularity of conservative political ideologies. Despite all of these changes and developments, however, marriage still remains a future aspiration for most people. Based on research conducted related to family patterns in the past and most recent years, this analysis is going to predict the future of family models and patterns in 2035, highlighting differences related to race, ethnicity, and education.
While marriage rates have continued to decrease since the 1970s, most Americans still consider marriage to be a goal for their future. There are people choose to not get married for a number of reasons, but many Americans don’t get married or get married much later on in life simply because it is unobtainable financially. Marriage is extremely expensive, time consuming, and a huge commitment, and for these reasons people “...tie marriage ‘readiness’ to having a comfortable income, little to no debt, and a secure job” (Smock, P. & Schwartz, C., 2020). People want to be able to enjoy their wedding, have the celebration that “they’ve always dreamed of,” and still be living comfortably after it’s all said and done. Statistics taken from the U.S. Census Bureau in 1967 vs. 2018 showed that “In 1967, 70% of adults were living with a spouse compared with only 51% in 2018, and declines over the past decade matched those in the 1990s and 2000s” (Smock, P. & Schwartz, C., 2020). Other research has shown that this has only continued to decrease, as only “47% of households were headed by married couples” in 2024 (usafacts, 2025). With the current economic state of our country and struggles that so many middle-to-lower class citizens are facing right now, it can safely be assumed that these trends will only continue downwards, and the United States will most likely see 45% of married households or less.
For those who are still getting married in the United States today, their households may look quite different from the traditional family model. First, couples are getting married much later on in life, for reasons such as finances and more people, especially women compared to the past, wanting to focus on independence and building their career before concerning themselves with marriage. Research shows that in the 70s, women were on average getting married around 21 years old and men around 23 years old, however, by 2018 “women were on getting married around the age of 28 and men around the age of 30” (Smock, P. & Schwartz, C., 2020). Other studies have shown that this has stayed somewhat stagnant over the past few years, with the median age of marriage for men being 30.5 and 28.6 for women in 2022 (Bieber, C. J. D., 2024). Another drastic and notable change from the traditional family model is that there are many married households without children at all and there has been an overall decrease in fertility in the United States. Pew Research Center found that “In 1970, 67% of Americans ages 25 to 49 were living with their spouse and one or more children younger than 18. Over the past five decades, that share has dropped to 37%” (Aragao, C., Parker, K. & et al., 2023), which showcases the simultaneous increase in age of first marriage and decrease in rates of parenthood. Overall, the United States population has continued to get married later in life and having children is no longer a “requirement” to have a family. Due to the age of first marriage staying stagnant over the past few years, it can be assumed that there won’t be much change in that over the next 10 years. While it is likely that less household families in the future will continue to have children, it is not likely that the fertility rates will continue downwards, considering the overturning of Roe v. Wade and the criminalization of abortions in many states. It is more likely than anything that the United States will see an increase in childbirths out of wedlock over the next 10 years, considering that has already been on the rise (Aragao, C., Parker, K. & et al., 2023).
The national legalization of same-sex marriage from the ruling of Obergefell v. Hodges in 2015 completely changed the way our society viewed families and “what constituted a family.” Same-gender family dynamics challenge traditional gender norms and ideals, and many studies have been conducted relating to the structure of same-gender families and how gender roles apply differently and similarly to different-gender couples. The National Institute of Health found that “from 2016 to 2017, the number of married same-gender couples increased from 486,994 to 547,000” (Smock, P. & Schwartz, C., 2020). The Williams Institute at UCLA School of Law also found that “as of June 2025, there are an estimated 823,000 married same-sex couples in the U.S.” (UCLA, 2025). The number of same-gender married couples has only continued to increase over the years, but it is important to note that same-gender couples are facing many of the same economic challenges that different-gender couples are dealing with. Due to this, there may be a stagnation in the rate of same-gendered married couples over the next 10 years as well.
Mothers entering the workforce post WWII was the catalyst for changes in family ideals and household structures. However, things are still not nearly as “egalitarian” as they should be. There are many marriages today that have a woman as the primary breadwinner and many others where both partners make the same amount of money in a dual-income household. Over the past 50 years, “the share of women who earn as much as or significantly more than their husband has roughly tripled” (Fry, R., Hurst, K, et al., 2023). Even with this increase in financial equality within the household women still carry a much heavier load when it comes to household work, such as cooking and cleaning, and childcare, and men spend much more time on leisure and work, even when their wife is the primary breadwinner of the household. These gender norms are still very prevalent in households across the country; however, interviews and studies have shown that most Americans actually believe that both parents should be equally focused on work and home/childcare. While mothers are still taking on most of the childcare and housework, there are many households today where fathers are the primary caretakers of their children and/or a stay-at-home father. In the next 10 years in 2035, there will still be many households with mothers who are the primary caretakers of their children; however, it is also likely that we will continue to see an increase in the number of stay-at-home fathers as the primary caretakers.
Divorce and cohabitation rates have been heavily on the rise right along with the strong decline in marriage and fertility rates. With women entering the workforce, many of them found their independence and made the decision to leave their marriages, most of them likely being abusive in some way. Today, the divorce rates are “43% of first marriages end in divorce, 60% of second marriages, and 73% of third marriages” (Bieber, C. J. D., 2024). There are many reasons why people choose to get divorced, such as lack of commitment from their partner, domestic abuse, and infidelity. While these factors are going to continue into years to come, it is likely that there won’t be a huge decrease in the divorce rates in 2035 simply due to financial constraints. Divorce costs couples “on average $7,000 to dissolve their union” (Bieber, C. J. D., 2024), which may lead to many couples choosing to postpone their divorce or push to fix their marriage. Cohabitation rates have also seen a huge increase over the past decades, and living together is no longer seen solely as a steppingstone to marriage. As of 2014, over 70% of people getting married had lived with their spouses beforehand” (Smock, P. & Schwartz, C., 2023). These rates will most likely continue to increase, especially for those who are economically challenged, as many people live together in order to afford rent and other necessities. 
By 2035, the United States is expected to see continued developments and changes to the various family models that we have today. Using data from the past and current data, this analysis attempted to predict the “future of family” in the United States, covering multiple different atmospheres. These atmospheres included women’s involvement in the workforce, age of marriage, fertility, divorce and cohabitation rates, and the development of same-gender families. While many of these predictions are based on this data, it is important to recognize the impact of the current political climate and of the impacts of the media and outside forces. Things like this that are less predictable and constantly developing could lead to strong falters in these predictions. Our society is constantly growing, changing and learning new things, forever encouraging changes within social institutions and societal structures, family always being the most important.

What is Justice? 
The author of “Justice: What is the right thing to do?” is an American political philosopher and professor at Harvard University named Michael Joseph Sandel. This book is a New York Times bestseller that explores political philosophy and moral dilemmas by applying theoretical and analytical thinking to real-world issues. Sandel invites the readers to engage in reasoned debate about justice and the common good in society. He challenges the shallowness of debates focused solely on personal gain or individual liberty, arguing for a third basis: the impact on the common good. In “Justice: What is the right thing to do?”, it focuses on and examines different philosophical approaches to justice, including those of Aristotle, Kant, Mill, and Rawls, to understand contrasting ideas. While engaging with complex philosophy, the book is written in a lively and accessible way, making it suitable for a broad audience interested in making sense of politics, morality, and their own beliefs. 
Chapter 1, “Doing the Right Thing,” of “Justice: What is the right thing to do?” talks about the central question of justice: how should we decide what’s right? He uses real-world problems and dilemmas to depict this, for example, his trolley problem, Hurricane Charley, or the Afghan goatherds. He uses these examples to show three main approaches to justice: maximizing welfare (utilitarianism), respecting freedom (libertarianism), and promoting virtue/common good (Aristotelian traditions). The runaway trolley dilemma proposes the question of saving one life or saving five when the solution is in hand. The brakes on the trolley stop working, and there are two groups on the track. You can pull the lever and move the trolley to the right, killing one worker and sparing five. A little bit later into the story it proposes another question: if you are just watching from a distance and see a bigger man standing there, you could push him onto the tracks and avert this disaster. In my opinion, I would not push this man onto the tracks, knowing in doing this I just killed him and put myself into a bigger situation. I would just let the train go, knowing I could not do anything aligning with my morals. It would be on my guilty conscience that I just killed this man when I could have removed myself from the situation and not done anything. Obviously this is a hard and terrible situation, knowing you could have people but at the loss of others. 
In chapter 2, “The Greatest Happiness Principle/Utilitarianism,” it speaks about utilitarianism, defining justice as maximizing overall happiness or pleasure. Sandel explores strengths like simplicity and impartiality and weaknesses like knowing utilitarianism can justify sacrificing individuals, ignores rights, and undervalues higher ideals. Like, for example, the lifeboat story when there were four stranded sailors, and when the cabin boy got sick, the group killed and ate him. They claimed they did this out of necessity to survive and promote the general well-being of keeping the majority alive. Bentham, an English moral philosopher, founded the doctrine of utilitarianism to maximize happiness. Mill contradicts this idea, thinking refinement emphasizes quality of pleasures and liberty as essential to well-being. Chapter 3, “Do We Own Ourselves?/Libertarianism,” goes hand in hand with this. Libertarianism holds that individuals own themselves and their labor, so government oversight should be minimal—protecting life, property, and contracts. Sandel examines issues in the book like taxation as it is seen as forced labor, drug laws, and military conscription. For libertarianism, taxation is seen as forced labor because “if you are taxed, you can always choose to work less and pay lower taxes; but if you are forced to labor, you have no such choice.” Basically saying that people are forced to pay the government money, and it should be voluntary; if they wanted to pay and help the community, they would. The tension arises between absolute self-ownership and the social responsibilities that come with living in a community. Personally, it's hard for me to lean one way completely because in certain situations I could agree with either. I do think that taxes should be something everyone has to pay and should not be voluntary because it helps the majority, but I also don’t think some people should be sacrificed unwillingly to help the majority.
Chapter 4, “Hired Help / Markets and Morals,” asks whether everything should be up for sale. Sandel considers markets in controversial areas like military service substitutes, surrogate motherhood, and organ sales. He argues markets aren’t neutral: they can corrupt or degrade the value of certain goods and can create inequality by allowing the wealthy to “buy” advantages. One story that gets brought up to demonstrate this is “Pregnancy for Pay,” which is about a family paying a surrogate to have their baby since they can’t. It comes up with the question of if they are paying for the baby itself, which is baby-selling, or paying for the service of having the baby. Mary-Beth is the surrogate for the Sterns, and eventually when she has the baby for them, she tries to take it, but they go to court and fight for custody of the child. The baby ultimately went to the Stern family for the child's sake. In my opinion, I think they were paying Mary Beth for the service of having the child and the burden of carrying it to term for them, not for the baby itself. Also, I think it is a good idea that the child ended up in the custody of the Sterns because they had a contract set and paid Mary Beth; not only that, but she tried to flee with the child. 
“What Matters Is the Motive/Immanuel Kant” is the name of chapter 5, and it focuses on how Kant shifts focus from consequences to motives. Thinking that the only truly moral actions are those done from duty, guided by reason, and acting only on principles you would have as universal laws, treat people as ends, not means. Justice, in Kant’s eyes, requires respecting human dignity, not maximizing welfare or efficiency. He believes that actions represented as good in themselves are necessary: “Kant contrasts hypothetical imperatives, which are always conditional, with a kind of imperative that is unconditional: a categorical imperative” (pg. 112). I don't fully believe in Kant's ideas; for example, if an axe murderer was coming after my friend, I would lie about where they were. I would want my friend to survive, and I would not want to be the reason they got found and killed. There are reasons to lie sometimes, which Kant doesn’t believe. In Chapter 6, “The Case for Equality / John Rawls,” Rawls argues that justice is fairness. Using the “veil of ignorance” thought experiment, he claims people would choose two principles: equal basic liberties for all, and inequalities are just only if they benefit the least advantaged, involving social and economic equality. Kant and Rawls agree on the importance of universal principles, autonomy, and justice over consequences. Rawls ideas challenge libertarianism and utilitarianism by emphasizing fairness over luck or efficiency.
In Chapter 7, “Arguing Affirmative Action,” Sandel examines debates over affirmative action in college admissions. He outlines three justifications: correcting past injustice, promoting diversity, and promoting meritocracy. Critics argue it violates fairness or demeans achievement. For example, the Hopwood study is based on Cheryl Hopwood, a white applicant who was denied admission to the University of Texas Law School despite strong academic credentials. She argued that the school’s affirmative action policy discriminated against her, since minority applicants with lower grades and test scores were admitted. In my opinion, I think there are many different things that go into college applications that could be bigger than test scores and academics. Like their essay, extracurriculars, athletics, etc. Even if they were even on that standpoint and just differed in academics, I think the school is still entitled to choose who they want if they want to include more diversity. She did not have to go to this college, and college is a choice and privilege for many people. The discussion highlights deeper questions: what counts as merit, and should admissions reflect individual achievement or social purposes?
In chapter 8, “Who Deserves What?/Aristotle,” it kind of goes along with chapter 7, saying that Aristotle sees justice as giving people what they deserve, but this depends on the purpose or telos of the good being distributed. For example, the purpose of a university is cultivating knowledge, not rewarding legacy or wealth. Justice thus requires reasoning about virtue and the common good, not just neutral principles. In the book, they talk about the story of Callie Smartt, a high school freshman with cerebral palsy. She was a cheerleader during the football season, but at the end she got kicked off for not being able to perform the gymnastics and tumbling required to be on the team. “Callie’s story raises two questions. One is a question of fairness. Should she be required to do gymnastics in order to qualify as a cheerleader, or is this requirement unfair, given her disability?” (pg. 149). My response to this question would be that it's not fair to kick her off the team when she has an abundant amount of school spirit and shows her worth of staying on the team. Just because she cannot do flips or tricks, she can still cheer the team on while her other cheerleading teammates fulfill the requirements. 
Chapter 9, “What Do We Owe One Another?/Dilemmas of Loyalty,” explores moral duties rooted in ties of loyalty, community, and identity, such as family, country, or religion. Sandel contrasts universal moral principles with particular obligations, for example, patriotism and solidarity. He raises the question: are we only bound by impartial and unbiased principles, or also by the “moral weight” of our personal attachments? Part of this chapter asks the question of if the government and people should apologize for the sins and wrongdoings of our predecessors. Even if we did not personally harm those, and it was the previous generations, we should still acknowledge and apologize for it. For example, slavery—although slavery is not a thing anymore, racism still exists, and we can acknowledge that so that history does not repeat itself. Finally, the last chapter, “Justice and the Common Good,” argues that justice cannot be morally neutral. Decisions about justice inevitably involve debates about virtue, purpose, and the common good. Sandel critiques liberal neutrality, like Rawls and libertarianism, and concludes that a just society must engage in moral and civic dialogue about what kind of people and community we want to be. This chapter brings up one point about justice and the common good, talking about how John F. Kennedy and Barack Obama had very opposing ideas about religion in politics. John F. Kennedy felt that even though he was Catholic, he was not going to base any of his ideas or concepts on religion, knowing people would disagree. On the other hand, Obama thought that his Christianity should be involved in his politics, since the majority of America would be influenced and believe the same as him. Personally, I think religion has no place in the government or politics, especially in America, knowing that we have such a diverse country and not everyone believes in religion or the same religion at all. I do understand where Obama was coming from, though, because both he and JFK were doing what would get them the most votes.
In the end, “Justice: What Is the Right Thing to Do?” pushes readers to wrestle with difficult questions about morality, fairness, and the common good. By exploring contrasting philosophies and applying them to real-world dilemmas, Sandel shows that justice is never simple and cannot be reduced to one principle alone. Instead, it requires thoughtful reflection, open debate, and a willingness to balance personal freedom with responsibility to others. His work ultimately challenges us not only to think critically about what is right but also to consider the kind of society we want to build together.

I think some of the critiques with utilitarianism can be valid as well. One of the points that Sandel brings up is the violation of individual rights and reducing morality to a mere calculation. While I think I tend to lean in a more utilitarian way of thinking I think these are some great points. I think in some scenarios there’s more than just simply making the most amount of people happy. We need to look at the motive and intention behind certain situations. I also believe what one person might consider happiness might be different from what another might consider happiness. It’s all subjective. Another topic that Sandel addresses is libertarianism. He uses philosophers like Nozick to explain the specifics of what libertarianism is. The example that I resonated with is Michael Jordan. As a die-hard basketball fan who is also a Chicago Bulls fan, I thought that using Michael Jordan as an example really put this theory into perspective. During the 90’s, Jordan brought the NBA much more viewership and appealed to the global market. With this new spike in viewership, I think it was only fitting that Jordan be the highest paid player in the league. Nozick presents the idea that making Jordan pay 30% of his salary(taxation) is equivalent to stealing or forced labor. 
The main critique to this argument is the poor are more in need of the money and that Jordan isn’t playing alone on the court. For this scenario, I lean both ways but I’m slightly going to side with Nozieck. The Chicago Bulls didn't see nearly as much revenue when Michael Jordan decided to retire abruptly and play major league baseball. Almost all people were spending money to see Michael Jordan play, not Scottie or the rest of his teammates. While I do agree it wasn’t fair how big the discrepancy of pay was between Michael and his peers, I understand why it was the way it was. Now in terms of taxation, I don’t think it’s stealing to tax someone and help the poor out. The more money you make the more you're gonna get taxed. This is a system that I believe is fair because of how hard it is for lower class people to climb and succeed in this world. I also think most people who become billionaires did something unfair and immoral to achieve that amount of wealth(not all of them). A Boy Broken: Midterm Reflection
	“A Boy Broken”, written by Douglas J. Engelman in June of 2023, is a story about a father’s experience after his eldest son, Douglas Jr., is diagnosed with schizophrenia. The story takes the reader through firsthand events leading up to the diagnosis, the diagnosis itself, and how the Engelman family moved forward after not only Douglas Jr.’s (Doug’s) diagnosis, but also his death that occurred eight years later.
	In his work, Engelman (2023) shares his personal firsthand experiences with schizophrenia in order to help readers better understand the mental disorder. His goal, as I interpreted it, was to assist others who have been affected by a mental disorder diagnosis, whether it be personally, as a caregiver, or simply affecting someone close to you. He rawly describes his emotions, which allows others to relate to and not feel so ashamed or just upset with themselves when they feel those same emotions. He discusses the stigma surrounding mental disorders and why this stigma has to be broken in order for society to move forward. And, in order for individuals and their families to confidently be able to reach out for help and support during one of the hardest times of their lives. Engelman (2023) describes this stigma as “inhibiting recovery and a favorable life outcome for the person with mental illness” (p. 29). 



Theories and Stigma:
	Theories like the symbolic interactionist and labeling contribute to the overall stigma and perception of mental illness or disorder. Once born, individuals are expected to conform to the societal ideals of “normal” behavior. If a person goes against these societal norms, values, and beliefs, they face the consequence of being labeled “deviant”. Edwin Lemert, an American sociologist, divided this “deviant” label into two separate terms, primary deviance and secondary deviance. Primary deviance “is associated with non-normative behavior” (Engelman 2023:26). Engelman provides schizophrenia as an example. So, Doug being diagnosed with the mental disorder already put him in a box, labeling him deviant, though it was not his choice to not be “normal” according to society, just an unfortunate circumstance. Secondary deviance is when an individual assumes their deviant identity and acts out because of society’s prejudice towards them. In the book, we did not see secondary deviance in Doug; in fact, he worked diligently to be one of the ten percent with schizophrenia who go on to live a normal life. 
	Another American sociologist, Bruce Link, connected stigma to labeling theory. He claimed that “stigma of the label ‘mentally ill’ is internalized and imposes social stresses on the individual, to which the person adapts by implementing coping strategies such as concealing the condition…or the outright withdrawal of the individual from social interaction” (Engelman 2023:27-28). The stigma surrounding those who are deemed mentally ill makes an already difficult situation even more difficult for both the individual and their family. A Canadian sociologist, Erving Goffman, explained how stigma applied to the mentally disordered leads them to restricted social opportunities, and changes in self-identity” (Engelman 2023: 28). It is also brought up in the text that stigma impedes one’s ability to recover from a mental disorder.  
	Later on in this paper, it will be discussed how Doug overcomes this stigma associated with his schizophrenia diagnosis and goes on to receive treatment, respond very well to that treatment, land himself a job, and be able to live on his own (like many others with the disorder cannot).
	We see the author and his family also react to the stigma caused by his son’s diagnosis. Originally, Engelman (2023) tried to hide Doug’s diagnosis due to fear of what others would think of him as a parent, even though the diagnosis had nothing to do with his parenting. Engelman then dove into how he questioned if the diagnosis was his fault. If he had not divorced Doug’s mother, if he had not moved away, if he had been more present. But all of these what-ifs are not an explanation for how or why Doug ended up being diagnosed with the disorder. The only fact that truly mattered was how the author helped his son deal with the disorder. 
If it had not been for his unwavering support and love for his son, I do not think Doug would have been a part of that small ten percent that comes out on top, and is able to live normally (for the most part). It is truly admirable to be able to, what I felt was, experience just how much a father loves his son, how far he is willing to go, how much he is willing to do. And, in the end, it worked out beautifully; all of both Engelman and Doug’s hard work paid off.
Doug’s Story:
	At age twenty, Doug was diagnosed with drug-induced schizophrenia. Doug’s first psychotic break was witnessed by his sister Melissa. He was outside on the back porch, repeatedly yelling the phrase “Why do they have to die?” for ten minutes (Engelman 2023:6). Melissa was worried, so she called the police. Officer Thomas arrived on the scene and talked it out with Doug. The author reached out to Officer Thomas in hopes of finding answers to his questions. The officer relayed his belief that Doug may be schizophrenic and that he should be checked out by medical professionals. 
	The author’s first experience of realizing his son may be schizophrenic occurred when he picked Doug up the morning after the incident to go to breakfast. While in the car, Doug mentioned that two people, Wendy and Dave, were always with him. Doug said that Wendy was in the car with them when it was only the author in the driver’s seat and his son in the passenger seat. While in the car, Doug experienced severe pain in his abdomen. He claimed that Dave and Wendy could put their hands inside of him, and that was what was causing it. 
	Doug’s Uncle Harry, on his father’s side, was also diagnosed with schizophrenia in his early twenties. The family history, and as the author mentioned later on, Doug’s frequent smoking of marijuana could be attributed to the development of his disorder, but this question was not specifically answered. 
	Doug’s first experience in the medical field was at Loyola Medical Center’s Mental Health unit. His father dropped him off for intake there, and he was taken right into a thirty-day program. This is where Doug was first medicated for his disorder, and he was responding well, saying it was “helping him think straight” (Engelman 2023:63). His first days at the facility were spent in solitary where he was heavily medicated. He then underwent individual and group therapy sessions, and eventually exposure to the rest of the patients in the facility. 
	After the month at Loyola, Doug was moved to John J. Madden Mental Health Center. Madden allowed Doug more professional care, more exposure to experimental anti-psychotics, and more therapy (Engelman 2023:65). Once in the care of Madden, Doug had his first experience with a group home, where he ended up staying for nine months. During his stay at the group home, Doug experienced ups and downs. His money was taken from him, and later on, he was threatened. This threat caused Doug to return home to the author’s house one day, claiming he needed to leave Madden. 
	Three weeks after coming back to Madden from his father’s, that one night, Doug disappeared. It was not until three weeks after his disappearance that Doug reached out to his father. For three weeks, Doug was out on the streets, staying at Franciscan Outreach during the nights. After the phone call, Engelman (2023) went directly to pick up his son and brought him home. They had dinner, talked, and decided it would be best for Doug to move out of the group home. 
	Doug ended up moving into an apartment with an older man. At this apartment, Doug landed himself a job. After over half a year at this place, Doug decided he wanted to go back to Pittsburgh, where he was surrounded by family that he was missing. 
	When back in Pittsburgh, Doug had moved back in with his mother and was serviced by Chartiers Mental Health/Mental Rehabilitation Center. He stayed with his mother for two years before moving out and moving in with his sister Melissa, which lasted only for a year.
	Eventually, the author came to Pittsburgh to help with Doug’s situation along with his sister and mother. They found Doug an apartment where he faced some challenges. He was continuing to abuse weed and alcohol even though he knew it was bad for him to partake in them with his diagnosis. And he was not staying consistent with his medication. While at this apartment, and hanging out with old friends Chuck and Bob, Doug found himself frequently in trouble with the police. It was in his best interest that he move, so he did. 
	When Doug moved apartments, he ended up moving to a new mental health facility, Mercy Behavioral Health. It was at Mercy where Doug began to flourish more than ever before. His new therapist, Julie Gatti, helped him in ways he had not been helped before. Engelman (2023) noted that “It was clear she had reached him in a way that no one else had previously” (p. 123). Doug was getting a handle on his substance abuse during this time, and his progress with his overall diagnosis became even more prominent.
	Doug stayed in the area but moved into his own home, where he was approved for Section 8 housing. He had made such a nice life for himself, even regaining employment at his old high school job where he installed carpeting. With all of these amazing opportunities happening to Doug, he gained “a sense of purpose and optimism” that his father, the author, had not seen in years.
	The last time the author saw Doug in life was at Doug’s Uncle’s wedding. Doug was doing great. 
	The last time Doug and his father talked over the phone on December 16, 1988, things were really looking up for him. He called just “to say how great I’m doing. How happy I am” (Engelman 2023:135). Doug had plans to go back to school, but sadly, three days after their last call, Doug was killed in a tragic car accident.
Summary:
	During the eight years of living with schizophrenia, Doug became one of the ten percent to live a somewhat normal life. Tragically, that life was cut short. 
	This book delivers a sense of hope to its readers, whether they have experience with mental disorder or not, hope for families made up of mentally disordered individuals. With hard work and determination, people can overcome and be more than their disorder. 
	While reading the book, I felt certain aspects on a personal level. When I had my first depressive episode, I was too scared to admit it to my mother. I did not want her to blame herself that I no longer wanted to live. Eventually, I had to admit it to her. So, I think this book and how the author dealt with and supported his son through his entire diagnosis and life can help others struggling to get over the “shameful stigma” and reach out for support. If I had not already had my conversation with my mother, I most definitely would have after reading this book.

Source:
Engelman, Douglas J. 2023. A Boy Broken. Kindle Direct Publishing.

Projecting the Future of the 2035 Families: Trends and Transformations
Sociologists examine family change not only by documenting past and current trends, but also by imagining reasonable futures based on these patterns. The American family has been rapidly changing due to shifting cultural norms, economic conditions, and policy responses. For example, marriage rates and age at first marriage have changed (Herre et al. 2025, para. 10). Mothers' labor force participation has risen, while single-parent and one-person households have increased. Likewise, blended and cohabiting families have become more common, and a growth in households identifying as same-sex couples. There is current evidence to project how these trends may reconstruct what a "typical" family life looks like by the year 2035.
Multiple evidence-based trends can help us understand what 2025 to 2035 might look like, for example, regarding marriage and partnerships. After decades of declining marriage rates and increasing ages at first marriage, and a resulting drop-off in marriage counts due to the 2020 pandemic, marriage counts have recovered for the time being (Herre et al. 2025, para. 23). Trends in the data still show a smaller percentage of people marrying at an earlier age, and the share of people currently living unpartnered or cohabiting, rather than marrying, is greater than in the mid-20th century. Recent analysis has found marriage rates in the low ratings across the entire US. Still, the marriage rate is offset by a much greater share of adults who are either unmarried or cohabiting without marriage (Buck et al., 2024, para. 6-8)
Women's involvement in labor has increased mostly during the late 20th century, and even though the overall female labor force participation rate has been changing in the 2010s and early 2020s, mothers of children of school age still experience relatively high labor force participation rates, and many families depend on two earners in the family. Recent Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) data show that about three-quarters of mothers of children under 18 are in the labor force (Bureau of Labor Statistics, 2023, para. 9)
The amount of children living with a single parent rose steeply in the decades after 1960; by the 2010s–2020s era, approximately one quarter of children had spent time in a household with a single parent, and one-person households accounted for an increasing share of all households. However, some recent data show slight declines at times in the share of single-parent households (Barrett, 2022, para. 3-5). Blended families and cohabiting couples are more typical today than in earlier generations. Households headed by married same-sex couples and by same-sex cohabitating couples are also common today and increasing (Scherer, 2022, para. 1-4)
Marriage is becoming less of a universal life experience and is now just one way to experience cohabitation among many forms that are sanctioned. For instance, many adults who form long-term partnerships will continue to delay legal marriage until later in life, once they have established careers or financial resources. Others will cohabit long-term without legal marriage, particularly when there are weakened legal and economic incentives to marry, or when couples actively prefer cohabitation over marriage to maintain flexibility  (Fry, 2025, para. 2). Levels of overall marriage at any age will be lower than in mid-twentieth-century America. 
By 2035, most mothers will be engaged in paid work, but the nature of that work will be more diverse. The continued increase of remote and hybrid workplaces, greater acceptance of flexibility in employer expectations, and technological shifts will enable parents to combine paid work and caregiving responsibilities with greater flexibility. Nevertheless, wage inequality, employer-provided benefits, and unequal access to quality childcare will still constrain the choices of mothers in less-than-ideal financial situations (Bureau of Labor Statistics, 2025, p. 2). The data from the Bureau of Labor Statistics on labor force participation rates for mothers with school-aged children, including findings from a recent survey indicating a significant amount of interest in telework, would also support these assumptions (Bureau of Labor Statistics, 2025, p. 2-3). Data show that women who are married, pregnant, or have children under age 3 are less likely to be employed in their marriages (Bureau of Labor Statistics, 2025, p. 14). This is because mothers are still seen as the family's caregivers and are expected to be at home taking care of the child, rather than the man. 
Blended families and cohabitating multigenerational living arrangements are likely to be common adaptations to economic pressures and shifting social norms. Some young adults will remain in or return to their parental homes for more extended periods, while some older adults will live with adult children due to economic constraints, health needs, or preference. Rising census data on one-person households, cohabitation households, and multi-type households indicate this pluralization of family structures (Barrett, 2022, para. 3)
By 2035, households headed by same-sex couples will represent an appreciably larger share of family types, as they have continued to grow alongside the expansion of legal recognition and social legitimacy in the 2010s and 2020s. There are legal and social barriers; diversity in race/ethnic backgrounds, income, and parental status will only increase. Further evidence from census records of the continued increase in same-sex married households indicates this trend should persist. (Hays & Minkin, 2025, para. 3-10)
The future of families will differ. Families with higher incomes and better education will have more opportunities to avail themselves of flexible working hours, good child care, and housing that supports family stability and choice. On the other hand, lower-income families will continue to suffer from the same limitations as before; they will have unstable jobs, housing insecurity, and difficulties in finding affordable childcare that will not be available in their neighborhoods, which will lead to the rise of complex living arrangements and children with different fathers in some areas (Bureau of Labor Statistics, 2025, p. 4-6)
The shape of 2035 families will be altered by three important domains that can amplify trends: public policy, cultural change, and the technology/labor market. The expansion of publicly funded childcare, full paid maternity leave, and subsidized housing in the United States would mean that families from lower-income to high-income would have more options: in case of an economic risk, earlier childbearing would be less risky, mothers could still be in the labor force with lesser sacrifices, and single parents would get more help. On the other hand, if these policy areas stagnate, inequalities will worsen and choices will be reduced, which in turn will make it unavoidable for complex household arrangements to become survival strategies (Bureau of Labor Statistics, 2025, p. 6-14). If the public continues to take in different types of families, social institutions like schools, hospitals, and employers will adapt, thereby eliminating stigma and making it easier for unconventional families to live day to day. 
The​‍​‌‍​‍‌​‍​‌‍​‍‌ American family by 2035 will probably not go back to being a single dominant type. Instead, families will have plural, layered arrangements, resulting from delayed marriage. Maternal labor force participation will be high but uneven; the number of single-parent households will remain steady; more blended families will exist; and the visibility of same-sex families will be greater. The most important questions for scholars and policymakers are which policies and cultural changes will reduce inequality and, at the same time, help shape stable, healthy family lives in diverse households? Real-world evidence, as shown in data, suggests that the only thing left is society's choice in response to those trends.

Reflection Essay: A Boy Broken







When I first heard about my midterm assignment being based on the book, ‘A Boy Broken’ by Douglas Engelman, I was thinking it would be sadder with a family dynamic of son and father, but I never expected it to hold. as much power as it did. Engleman’s book carries more than just sadness; it carries love, truth, and suffering. While reading this book, I not only opened my mind up to the possibilities of mental illness and loss, but also what it means to have hope, to be strong, and to keep going when the future seems so terrifying. 

Engelman starts the story by sharing his fatherhood to a son who suffers with mental illness. The book shares about Engelman’s son having a psychotic breakdown. This means his mind stopped working the way it usually would. His son begins to see things and hear things that are not there or real. This unfortunate circumstance changed Engelman’s entire family dynamic that day. Engelman describes how he learns about how his son's future will now be altered; he shares how he tries to help him, talks us through the raw difficulties, treatments, therapy, and the hope he held on for things to get better. 
Ultimately, yes, they have good moments, some even giving more hope that his son will get better, the book takes a terrible turn and horrifying ending with his son unfortunately being killed in a car accident. Left with grief, sadness, and questions, this led Engelman to search for what this all meant for his life moving forward. 

I learned several things while reading Engelman’s, A Boy Broken, that I think any person would agree are important, especially for teenagers growing up and those who still seem to get stuck with the short end, figuring out how hard life can be. 
Starting off, mental illness is a severe problem someone deals with every day, and it is not to be dismissed. Before this book, I had dabbled in some anxiety prescriptions and investigated therapy for myself, however I was unaware of how serious mental illness could be and how much of your life it could take over, not just for you but for those around you as well. Engelman dives into his son’s mental illness and how it affects his family life, also how this was not something he could just “snap out of.” Mentally ill people not only are affected by themselves, but they affect those around them, the loving family, and friends by their side. Not grasping the idea of this can lead to misunderstanding, judgement, and fear. Seeing Engelman learn to listen, try to empathize with his son, and give him unconditional support even when it is scary and showed me how important it is to show grace to everyone and give kindness to all. 
Another lesson for me was that grief comes with life but does not have to end everything for you. Engelman deals with a tremendous loss towards the end and even the beginning of the book by losing his son to a mental illness. The end of the book led to Engelman’s sadness, confusion, and guilt. He tries his best to make sense of everything, he goes back and forth with questions in hopes of finding an answer, and he tries to find meaning. How to keep going in a way that supports not only his son, but others as well. He learns how to accept the idea that everything going on is out of his own hands and he cannot control it, no matter how hard he tries. I learned that grief, as horrible as it is, is not something that will last overnight. Grief is something linear, one day you feel good, and the next day you feel the same emotions twice as hard, like it had just happened again. Grief is something that changes you, something to carry with you every day, but also something that forces you to grow, something that helps you view life differently than before. 
Lastly, I was reminded of the importance of hope. The book is dark, but not all dark. It has moments where you feel optimism, moments where Engelman's son seems as though he is starting to get better, when small victories are apparent. These joyous moments made the hardest parts somehow feel heavier, because you see what it could be, which makes your losses hurt more. Hope gives you the strength needed to push yourself through to keep going. Engelman had a choice when his son was diagnosed. He chose to help him fight, even though his son’s future was unclear, showing that hope was helping him choose for his family. 

I was conflicted while reading this story, feeling all kinds of emotions, hope, love, loss, grief, pain, empathy, and optimism. Feeling for Engelman’s family, wondering if his son understood, if he was getting treated correctly. I was terrified when his son would get scared or begin to suffer more. I felt so much love and admiration for Engelman, knowing he was doing his best to understand, and giving his son the vulnerability, honesty, and love still given to him so deeply. 
I will be honest, I did get angry while reading, not at anyone in the story but just at society for not understanding mental illness as they should. Sometimes, those who are sick do not get the care they need, when treatment comes too late or is wrong. 
Something I felt connected by with the story was understanding when Engelman searched for answers as to why this had to happen and how he could have stopped it. Truthfully, I feelmoments like these more frequently than I would like to admit. I’m unsure as to why I feel like I am the root cause of a problem, but due to this feeling, I tend to always look for a way to fix things or to help things get better, in hopes that instead of ruining things, I am the reason they get better.

Some questions I was able to think about asking Engelman and his family while reading was, was it easy deciding to support your son with his mental illness? If someone you love was diagnosed with a mental illness, what are the limits with support? Would you still care for yourself? 
Engelman sometimes struggles with feeling like he could have done something differently, does he ever have peace with what he did do? Did he forgive himself for the things he could not do?
As Engelman is my professor this semester in class, was your son the only reason you starting teaching sociology with a mental illness? 
Thankfully in my situation, I have never had to lose someone to death just yet, out of curiosity and the upmost respect, how do you go on with life? How do you still honor your son, but still live your life?
This book showed me that life throws you curveballs and puts you through horrible tragedies to teach you something unclear at the moment but will eventually benefit you later on. 
People we love get hurt in ways we would never imagine, and we end up in situations we cannot fix. I did learn though that even though we are unable to fix things sometimes, we are always able to choose how we respond, you can choose to be kind, you can choose commitment, and you can choose hope. 
This book showed me that every family is different, and how every family deals with things, such as mental illness, is different. Love holds a lot but is not always enough. In this case, Engelman and his family needed understanding, professional advice, honest and sometimes hurtful conversations, and the courage to stay even when it is hard. Loss does not change how strong your love can be, love stays when it gets hard, love is honest, love is loud in a world that seems so quiet. 

A Boy Broken by Douglas J. Engelman is a strong but heartfelt book. It does not hide emotions; it does not pretend; it is loud. It gives you the reality of a demanding situation with an unsure future. It shows you the insight of what it looks like to go through pain, to stay when it is hard, to love when it hurts too much, and to still have hope when the world seems so shattered. 

I strongly feel as though this book gave me the knowledge to be more aware of others mental illness, their family life, society and the misconstrued belief of grief and loss. It reminds me that we may never truly know what someone else is going through. It reminds me to still give kindness to those who hurt me, to not judge others, and always lend a hand whenever I can. Most importantly, this book taught me that time is not guaranteed, and that I need to cherish my small victories and little moments, while I still can. “The Family” in Ten Years
Families in the United States have evolved significantly over the years. The nuclear family is no longer the only type of family accepted in society. Diverse families have become more common, including same-sex families, single-parent households, and interracial families. There are more women in the workforce and more men taking on caregiving roles. Marriage rates are declining, and people are deciding to have children later in life or not at all. Ten years from now, these things will only be more prominent. 
Marriage rates are declining and will only keep doing so. Only 47% of households are made up of married couples. In 1970 it was 71% (Census Bureau, 2024). People are starting to wait to get married for many reasons. Cohabitation is a lot more common. People are not waiting for marriage to move in together. If people do not need to be married to live together or to even have kids, there will not be as much of a rush to get married. Divorce rates are high. Around 40% of marriages will end in divorce, which is not too promising (Bailey, 2025). It is smart to be more cautious because weddings are expensive and so are divorces. People want to wait to be financially stable before getting married. Weddings can be expensive, and a lot of people look at them as more of a symbol of achievement and success and less as a right of passage. (Walsh, 2021). 
People are also waiting to have children or are planning on not having any at all. Just from 2012 to 2023 the total number of children people planned to have dropped from 2.3 to 1.8 (Hays, 2025). Having children is expensive. People are reaching financial goals, like moving out of their parents’ house and getting married, later in life, which means they are having children later because self-sufficiency is harder to achieve. This is because mortgage rates are up and so is unemployment. (Medaris, 2024). Childcare is expensive and most families cannot afford to have one parent not working. Some couples are scared to have children because of climate change. About 39% of young people are hesitant to have children because of climate concerns, according to a study by Caroline Hickman, et al. Some women are even scared to reproduce since Roe v. Wade was overturned. They feel their reproductive rights are being threatened and bringing a daughter into that world is scary for them (Medaris, 2024). About 44% of adults below the age of 50 say they most likely will not have any kids at all (Brown, 2021). Women also may not want to take on the responsibility. Women are normally the parent that takes on emotional role, which can take a toll on someone. Even if the child is not part of a single-parent household, there is still a possibility that both parents work, so there is still help needed in taking care of the child. Midterm reflection
The Transformative Moment
The Reality of Mental Illness
Through the memoir, Engelman recounts detailed and at times terrifying descriptions of his son's psychiatric breakdowns, including terrifying hallucinations and the constant threat of relapse. These descriptions are not just narrative but portals into the everyday life of serious mental illness. The writer's account of the "ups and downs" that characterize the journey of struggle with mental illness is all too recognizable to anybody who has witnessed a loved one’s struggle through psychological distress. Engelman's willingness to account for the disarray, confusion, and devastation of each episode highlights the cost of emotional anguish that such episodes exact on both the sufferer and the support network. By pursuing the point of desperation, hope, and strength that occurs, the memoir enables readers to understand the nuance of mental illness as it plays out in the moment, so that the story is not merely that of an individual family but a symbol for many others who fight similar struggles.
The power of the book lies in its refusal to sentimentalize or trivialize the experience of mental illness. Engelman presents to us the reality of watching a child endure diseases that defy easy explanation and quick fixing. His account resists the shame that so often clings to mental illness without negating the real challenge of figuring these problems out as a family. By showing the truth of everyday uncertainty, emotional exhaustion, and moments of hopelessness, Engelman provides an image of mental illness that is both genuine and compassionate. He invites readers to move beyond stereotypes or misconceptions and instead bear witness to the courage and perseverance it takes for both the patient and the family members. In doing so, the memoir is an effective instrument of empathy, opening up a discourse regarding the need for care, consciousness, and cultural change when it comes to mental healthcare.
The Burden on Family Systems
Maybe the most powerful aspect of "A Boy Broken" is its description of how mental illness affects entire family systems. Engelman does not at all isolate the experience within his son's personal struggles but illustrates how his son's illness reconfigures the emotional, logistical, and psychological environment of everyone around him. The family will be forced to navigate their lives each day, now colored by doubt, vigilance, and worry, a climate in which each member's needs and wants can become secondary to the resolution of the crisis.
Mental illness has ripple effects far beyond the person. Families are forced to recreate their schedules, expectations, and even sense of self. Plans once taken for granted can be replaced by fear, worry, and a general sense of uncertainty. Engelman's story shows that wives, brothers, and sisters, and mothers all feel feelings of guilt, helplessness, or bitterness as they work to care for the family member in trouble. This emphasis can lead certain members of the family to feel left out or excluded, as their own emotional demands take a back seat to the pressing demands of the mental health crisis.
Secondary trauma affects the cost sustained by those who care for someone with serious mental illness and is a recurring theme. Engelman speaks of deep sorrow and concern, not only for the health of his son, but for stability in the family and as a husband and father. Predictability and normalcy in the family generally lead to family mourning for the loss of an "ordinary" life. His observations closely reflect scholarly interpretations of family systems theory, which suggests that when one part of the system is debilitated by chronic illness or psychological distress, the entire system must compensate. In some instances, this adjustment also brings about beneficial restructuring, as families become more empathetic, communication becomes more robust, and new coping mechanisms are developed in response to adversity.
Moreover, Engelman's openness about revealing instances of conflict, misunderstanding, and exhaustion among family members shows the very human instances of caregiving. He is practical in understanding that caregiving for one who has a serious mental illness is not merely a labor of love but occasionally a source of frustration, fear, and tension. These accounts cut through cultural myths of unyielding strength and unbreakable togetherness, providing an honest account of the frailties and complexities that emerge during periods of adversity.
The memoir also provokes reflection about wider social issues. Family members also have to cope not only with the in-house issues of sickness but with external pressures—such as stigma from neighbors, friends, or even within the healthcare system. Engelman shows how these external pressures serve to build isolation on the part of families, intensifying distress and making the journey even more challenging. And yet, among these challenges, families can also find unexpected resilience. In mutual support, in moments of connection, and in a determination to keep going, many families—like Engelman's—build a new, though imperfect, path ahead.
Lastly, Engelman's honesty in the book is an important service to readers in that it reveals both the burdens and the bonds that psychiatric illness may impose upon a family. His book is an important contribution to mental health literature, extending consideration beyond clinical or personal records to encompass the entire family system and how it learns, breaks, and heals under stress.
The Search for Meaning Through Stoic Philosophy
With the death of his son in a car accident, Engelman embarks on a difficult path of discovery, finding solace in the philosophical principles of Stoicism as a way of coping with and surviving loss. This solution is a great model not just for insight into the situation of loss but also for living with integrity and purpose even in the middle of overwhelming loss. Engelman's tale demonstrates the Stoic idea that even things like becoming ill or dying by mishap are typically beyond our control in the external world, but our responses to such things lie within our control.
Death and suffering are met head-on with conviction by the Stoics. Grieving is acknowledged as a human, natural emotion and not something repressed or denied, but Stoic philosophers insist on resignation in pain as part of the tapestry of life. For Engelman, the process is embracing the pain and not refusing to acknowledge it, as one focuses on positive aspects: taking care of loved ones who survived, seeking assistance, remembering past experiences, and attempting to tell the truth after destruction.
One of the fundamental tenets of Stoicism outlined in the memoir is what is within our control and what is not. We have no control over altering fate, warding off all disaster, or halting mortality, but we do control engaging with trouble with intelligence and compassion. Engelman's ability to confront his grief head-on, and to make productive inferences from it on his own behalf and others', serves to validate the philosophy in life.
In addition, Stoic thought promotes the cultivation of gratitude for what is lost as opposed to mourning what is lost in absence. Seneca, another leading Stoic, promoted consideration of the beauty of being together and how those no longer with us shaped us, as compared to allowing absence to cheapen lived moments and the plenitude of memories. This helps to convert mourning into an even deeper love of the ephemeral nature of life.
Engelman's own case also reveals that Stoicism is not a denial of emotions, but a healthy working through of them in the moment. Mindfulness practice, present moment living, and acceptance of impermanence are all coping mechanisms for loss. Accepting what can’t be changed becomes part of an everyday coping mechanism to continue onward. By interweaving these practices, Engelman shows how philosophical examination can help us transform loss into wisdom and resistance and new purpose, neither forgetting but internalizing it as a necessary part of the human experience. Thus, "A Boy Broken" is not merely a survival guide to tragedy but a guide to drawing on loss as fuel for growth, empathy, and self-awareness. Engelman's embracing of Stoicism provides the language and protocol to those who are traversing through grief.

	Jeremy Bentham an English philosopher is known as the father of modern utilitarianism where he was known to critic both judicial and political instructions through defining fundamental concepts of ethics (John P. & Brian, 2025). Moreover, Bentham held the belief that the ultimate moral principle is the maximization of general welfare, collective happiness, and the overall balance of pleasures over pain. Utilitarianism advocates for wealth distribution, positing that those with greater financial capacity can aid those in less favorable economic conditions, subsequently improving their overall welfare. Another example, pulled from his book, Sandel presents the lifeboat case, a scenario involving four English sailors adrift in a small lifeboat in the South Atlantic, who were then rescued days later (Sandel 18). Upon their rescue, only three of the four members had survived, as one crew member confessed to having eat a fellow crew are due to starvation; the surviving sailors were then taken transported back to England to be tried for their crimes (Sandel 18). Sandel presented this scenario to illustrate that Bentham and other utilitarians would condone the sailors’ actions, as their philosophy prioritizes maximizing overall happiness. The sailors in question were affected from extensive famine. If sacrificing one sailor benefits the survival of the other crew mates, their actions are morally justified. Those who condemn the sailors’ actions would be unjust. In the following section, Sandel will present a counterargument and philosophy to the utilitarian perspective.
