Why the Greatest Happiness Principle still persuades me
In practice, this maps onto how many of us already reason when stakes are high. Hospitals triage. Governments budget. Even in ordinary life I allocate time and attention where they do the most good—helping a teammate who’s struggling before polishing a slide that’s already fine, or donating to a malaria charity that demonstrably saves lives rather than a vanity cause that merely makes me feel generous. Utilitarianism tells me I’m not cynical for thinking about numbers; I’m responsible.
Mill’s insistence on qualitative differences in pleasures—his “better to be Socrates dissatisfied than a fool satisfied”—also matters. It answers a caricature Sandel notes: utilitarianism is not addicted to shallow pleasures so much as committed to human flourishing broadly conceived. If reading, making music, or building a fair institution predictably deepens lives, then a utilitarian can rank those goods higher because they reliably produce more and richer happiness.
The best objections bite—and change how I apply utility
Where Sandel presses hardest is also where my own view softened. The first worry is about rights. If maximizing the balance of happiness could justify punishing an innocent person to quell a riot, we sense the calculus has gone wrong. Similarly, we recoil at throwing the “fat man” off the bridge in the trolley problem even if it would stop the train. These cases remind me that some actions are wrong not only because of what they cause but because of what they are—they use a person merely as a means. Mill tries to address this by building rights into the utility calculus (societies that protect rights do better overall), but the thought experiment exposes a limit: in extreme cases, rights look like side constraints, not merely rules of thumb.
The second worry is about measuring the unmeasurable. Sandel discusses cost-benefit calculations that put dollar values on human life—the Ford Pinto case has become emblematic. While some valuation is unavoidable in policy (every speed limit and drug approval implies risk trade-offs), Sandel is persuasive that certain ways of doing the math can degrade what we value. If a spreadsheet treats a vulnerable group’s suffering as a small externality, we haven’t just made a calculation; we’ve missed a moral reality. This pushes me toward rule utilitarianism: instead of justifying each act by its immediate payoffs, I favor rules that, if generally followed, predictably maximize well-being while protecting persons against being sacrificed in the name of efficiency.
Libertarianism, obligation, and why negative rights matter yet don’t settle the question
Sandel’s neighboring chapter on libertarianism made me appreciate the moral power of negative rights—the idea that others are obligated not to interfere with what I own and how I live, so long as I don’t harm them. Libertarianism dignifies consent and bodily autonomy: no one may conscript my life plans for their purposes.
I agree with that much. Yet utilitarianism warns me not to stop there. Libertarian freedom can ignore structural harms that are invisible if we fixate only on non-interference. A society that refuses to tax wealth to fund basic healthcare might pride itself on respecting self-ownership, but the predictable misery that follows is a moral cost we can count. This is where Sandel’s examples involving civil rights and equal access resonate: sometimes the best way to protect everyone’s negative rights over time is to invest in conditions that enable real options now. Freedom without capabilities rings hollow.
Rawls’s difference principle as a friend, not a foe, to utility
I read Rawls’s veil-of-ignorance device as a utilitarian ally. Behind the veil, we don’t know whether we’ll be born into wealth or poverty, health or disability. In that uncertainty, it seems rational to choose social rules that maximize the floor, not just the average. Rawls’s difference principle—arrange inequalities so they benefit the least advantaged—can be reframed as a risk-averse version of maximizing expected well-being. Large gains for those already well-off often return less happiness than smaller gains for those in severe need, because of diminishing marginal utility. So a safety net isn’t charity; it’s a predictable way to make the overall sum of well-being larger, in line with utilitarian aims, while also respecting persons by ensuring basic capabilities.
Admissions, merit, and telos: what are colleges for?
Sandel’s line that “admission is not an honor bestowed for superior merit or virtue” forced me to examine a comfortable story. If a seat at a university is simply a prize for individual excellence, then fairness looks like perfect rank ordering by scores. But Sandel reframes the practice through Aristotle’s telos: to decide who should be admitted, first ask what the institution is for. If a college exists to create certain kinds of learning communities, to train citizens, to pursue research, and to serve the public good, then it may justly select a class that advances those purposes, not merely the highest test scores.
From a utilitarian angle, this isn’t a betrayal of fairness; it’s a broader outcomes question. A class with genuine diversity of background and experience often yields better learning and better service to the public—consequences that matter. But Sandel’s caution helps: if we treat admission as pure social engineering, we risk instrumentalizing applicants for institutional goals. The sweet spot, I think, is to align individual opportunity with the mission’s social payoffs—a rule-utilitarian compromise that avoids fetishizing “merit” while preserving respect for applicants as ends in themselves.
Markets and the Baby M case: the utilitarian case for guardrails
Sandel’s discussion of surrogacy (and Elizabeth Anderson’s critique) captures another utilitarian tension. On one side, allowing willing adults to enter contracts like surrogacy can increase overall happiness: infertile couples find families, gestational carriers are compensated, and the arrangement is consensual. On the other side, certain market logics can corrupt meanings and produce subtle harms—turning parenthood into a commodity, exerting pressure on economically vulnerable women, or treating a child as the object of purchase. A purely act-utilitarian defense—if both parties consent and the outcome is net positive, it’s fine—can miss long-run effects on dignity and social trust.
My takeaway is again rule-based. A regulated surrogacy regime—cooling-off periods, independent counseling, clear parentage rules, bans on coercive contracts, fair compensation, and robust protections for the surrogate’s health—predictably produces better outcomes over time than either prohibition or laissez-faire. It keeps faith with the utilitarian aim (more families, less suffering) while honoring the non-fungible values at stake.
Obligations to strangers: the demanding edge of utility
If there is a part of utilitarianism that scares me, it is how demanding it can be once we recognize the scale of need. In the spirit of Peter Singer’s “shallow pond,” Sandel gently pushes readers to see that distance and numbers don’t erase obligation: if I would ruin my shoes to save a drowning child nearby, why wouldn’t I forgo luxuries to save children far away? A consistent utilitarianism challenges my comfort. It demands giving effectively, voting for policies that reduce global suffering (pandemic preparedness, climate mitigation), and shouldering fair taxes to fund programs that prevent predictable harms.
This is where a utilitarian lens becomes not only personal but political. Cost-effective health interventions (vaccines, bed nets), emissions policies that prevent catastrophic harms, and housing rules that reduce homelessness all pass a straightforward maximizing test. Sandel’s broader tour of justice reminds me that this is what politics is for—to make the trade-offs explicit, to argue about the values we honor, and to choose the rules that leave the fewest people worse off.
Where I draw the line: utility with side constraints
So where does this leave my self-description? I’m still a utilitarian because I think outcomes matter morally, and pretending otherwise often just hides whose outcomes we’re ignoring. But I’m a utilitarian who has learned from Sandel to value three constraints:
Rights as real limits, not just heuristics. We should adopt rules that refuse to sacrifice basic liberties even when a short-term calculus tempts us. Societies that keep those side constraints tend to do better anyway—and, more importantly, they respect persons as inviolable.
Telos as a guide to design. Before maximizing, ask what the practice is for. You can’t optimize a university, a marriage, or a court unless you honor its purpose. Otherwise, utility talk becomes blind to meaning and invites corruption of value.
Distribution matters. Because of diminishing marginal utility, how benefits and burdens are distributed is central to the sum of well-being. Rawls’s veil formalizes that insight, and it dovetails with utilitarianism’s concern for those at the bottom of the heap.
These constraints don’t abandon utility; they discipline it. They push me toward rule utilitarianism and toward institutional design that predictably raises human welfare while protecting the values we cannot price.
A few places I’m still wrestling
Sandel encourages critique, not closure, so I’ll end with the tensions I haven’t fully solved:
Measuring what matters. We can count lives saved or years in school. But how do we incorporate dignity, belonging, or meaningful work without either hand-waving or reductionism? Mill’s “higher pleasures” gesture in the right direction; I’m still looking for better proxies that policymakers can use without cynicism.
Preference formation. Utilitarianism often treats people’s preferences as the inputs. But many preferences are shaped by unjust structures or advertising. Should a planner maximize current preferences or the preferences people would hold under fair conditions? Rawls’s and Aristotle’s emphasis on education and virtue here is not a luxury; it’s the precondition for sensible maximization.
Partiality and personal ties. If I must always choose the option that produces the most total good, how much partiality to family and friends is morally permitted? A rule utilitarian answer—allow partiality up to the point where it predictably sustains valuable social roles—seems right, but the boundary is fuzzy.
Speech and offense. Libertarian non-interference protects expression; utilitarianism asks us to weigh harms. In polarized environments, it’s hard to separate transient discomfort (which may be the price of learning) from genuine degradation. Sandel’s classroom method—argue in good faith, name the values at stake—models a practice whose telos is mutual understanding, not victory.
Conclusion: maximizing with humility
Sandel’s book didn’t convert me away from utilitarianism; it matured it. I still think the core moral demand is to reduce suffering and increase flourishing impartially. But I now see more clearly that the best way to do that, over time, is not to run a ceaseless act-by-act calculus. It is to adopt rules and build institutions that honor persons, respect purposes, and attend to fair distribution—because human beings are not just containers of pleasure and pain but agents whose dignity and relationships generate the very goods we want to maximize.
Calling myself a utilitarian, then, is less a declaration of a calculator’s creed than a promise about attention: to count everyone, to face trade-offs honestly, and to choose policies that predictably leave fewer people worse off. Sandel’s tour through Rawls’s fairness, libertarian freedom, Aristotelian purpose, and market limits equips me with the humility to do that work better—aware of the edges where numbers mislead, where rights must stand firm, and where the telos of a practice tells us what “the most good” even means.

Traditional household’s vs modern trends 
Throughout American history, the family has been the foundation of moral order and social stability. However, over the past few decades, it has shifted dramatically. We have seen a decline in marriage rates, a rise in single-parent families, and a new wave of diverse family structures. These changes represent cultural changes towards individualism, gender equality, and economic change.  Many sociologists question what is lost when the traditional family structure weakens. As we look towards 2035, the difference between conventional households and modern family trends will define the new era of American family life. These modern family trends tend to emphasize flexibility and self-expression, where traditional households are grounded in commitment, stability, and shared values and viewpoints. These traditional viewpoints tend to be the strongest foundation for raising children and sustaining family and community life. 
            Over the last fifty years, marriages in America have shifted from being viewed as a social and religious obligation to a personal choice or lifestyle preference.  According to the Pew Research Center (2023), marriage rates have fallen to new historic lows.  With these declining rates, there has also been a new average age for first marriage, now 30. The reason for this shift is economic uncertainty, educational priorities, and a new cultural focus on personal fulfillment rather than collective responsibility. From a sociological viewpoint, this shift in declining marriages is a result of individualism (Cherlin, 2010). 
            By 2035, we can expect marriages to remain relevant but less tied to religious and communal expectations. There will be a rise in long-term partners and cohabitation among many Americans. However, research shows that stable marriages and two-parent households are better environments for young children. They tend to have better education, better well-being, and long-term economic stability (Wilcox & Marquardt, 2025). Even though our culture still gravitates toward flexible family arrangements, the traditional family and traditional marriage will remain the most stable and prosperous. 
            The nuclear family model, in which men traditionally worked and women managed the household, has largely disappeared. In 2024, more than 70% of mothers with children under 18 were in the workforce (U.S. Department of Labor, 2024). This statistic shows both the economic necessity and the progress that women have achieved. By 2035, all families will likely depend on two incomes, making dual-earner households the norm in the United States. 
            This new shift has created an interesting condition: on the one hand, we have growing equality between men and women in the labor market, which continues to contribute to empowerment and financial independence; on the other hand, it hinders traditional family roles and increases stress on work-life balance. This new expectation that both parents must try to contribute equally to income and still be active in childcare is what Sociologist Arlie Hochschild called the “Second Shift.”  Which is the unpaid labor of homestead and childcare responsibilities. 
            In a traditional household, labor is often divided more clearly. Each partner assumes specific responsibilities that support the family’s stability and lifestyle. While this modern gender flexibility is valuable, sociologists have found that households that maintain clear role expectations, whether traditional or egalitarian, tend to experience fewer problems and more satisfaction than those without structure (Wilcox 2020). In 2035, we may have new hybrid family models that balance traditional clarity with modern equality. Things like remote working and flexible scheduling could make it easier for families to share household and economic responsibilities. 
            In recent years, there has been a significant rise in single-parent and blended families. This is one of the most visible modern trends changing American households. In 1960, 9% of children lived in single-family homes; the figure is about 25% (U.S. Census Bureau, 2023). Economic and cultural factors have been the biggest reasons for these high divorce rates, nonmarital births, and delayed marriages. These families display resilience but often face significant sociological challenges. Research has shown that children raised by a single parent tend to face higher rates of poverty, lower academic performance, and increased behavior problems compared to those children raised in a stable traditional family. (McLanahan & Sandefur, 1994). 
            Through blended families, remarriage and cohabitation are expected to be even more common in 2035. These living arrangements bring unique strengths, such as expanded support networks, but also require navigating very complex and emotional times. These patterns underscore the value of family and stability in long-term commitment. Families grounded in faith, communication, and mutual sacrifice tend to manage change and transitions better than families guided by personal satisfaction. While modern, diverse families will continue to be the norm, the traditional household will remain the benchmark for consistency and child development. 
            The legalization of same sex marriage happened in 2015, and it marked a significant turning point for American family life. By 2035, it is expected that same sex families will be normalized within society. Sociologists say that this change expands the definition of the family, promotes acceptance, and reduces stigma. However, this evolution reflects a redefinition of family away from the biological and gender roles toward emotional and contractual ties. This recent trend shows how much our culture is shaping our understanding of family. 
            Technology will play a significant role in shaping the family in 2035. Things like artificial intelligence, remote work, and digital education are already altering how families interact. From one perspective, these tools can create more opportunities for parents to be more involved with their kids when working remotely. However, factors such as screen time, digital isolation, and the lack of face-to-face communication pose a significant threat to intimacy and family bonds. Economic pressure will continue to affect families with rising housing costs, student debt, and childcare expenses, all of which discourage marriages and the idea of having children among the young generation (Pew Research Center, 2023). 
            Traditional households, which tend to have clear roles, strong community ties, and shared faith, are more likely to be affected by these new threats. A family that prioritizes family meals and rituals creates a personal connection, which serves as a counterbalance to the digital world. By 2035, families that limit technology in their homes and daily lives could live a healthier, more connected life with all the modern conveniences and a deeper level of relationships. 
In 2035, the typical family will come in all shapes and sizes. There will be dual-income families, single parents, cohabiting couples, same sex parents, and blended families, all of which will remain present. Research still suggests that these families will maintain structure and stability while sharing moral values, and they will thrive. The traditional household in 2035 will look significantly different from one in 1950. It might have two working parents or rely heavily on technology, but it will still work. 
            Modern families will continue to work with flexibility and equality, but they will rediscover that freedom without order leads to instability. As these social norms fluctuate, family values will likely experience renewed appreciation among Americans. However, the sociological evidence will remain clear. Children and communities will benefit most from stable, committed two-parent households that prioritize responsibility and structure. Traditional households will continue to serve as a model of resilience and clarity in a rapidly changing world.

I enjoyed how you explained each stage through the lens of how you were processing the news of Doug’s diagnosis. I am sure that your grieving process upon the news of Doug’s death manifested itself in different ways. People grieve differently, but ultimately, similarly. While the stages are interesting, it is also important to note that they are not linear, and they never really “end.” 
	I appreciated the rawness of your explanation about your guilt in trying to hide your son’s schizophrenia from others. I feel like this is something that many people with someone close to them who has a mental disorder goes through, but feels like they can’t talk about. While I, specifically, have not dealt with someone close to me experiencing a severe mental disorder, I do have an uncle who experienced a severe drug addiction throughout my childhood. He has been sober and living alone for several years now, and my dad’s role in his recovery is not lost on me. My dad also displayed unconditional love, perseverance, healthy boundaries, and caretaking for his brother during his lifelong struggle with substance abuse. 
In that way, this novel kind of reminded me of the film “Beautiful Boy.” “Beautiful Boy” is based on a memoir written by a father as well. That movie, much like this book, details a father’s struggle with his son’s mental state, although in “Beautiful Boy,” the son is experiencing severe substance abuse and drug addiction. Additionally, there are ‘scenes’ in both in which the son goes missing and the father is helpless in his search for him. In both stories, the father figure searches for meaning among the grief he is experiencing by feeling like he is losing his son to something beyond his control. Both are profoundly moving and beautifully depict the relationship between fathers and sons. Furthermore, both are important in sharing real-life stories about struggles with mental health and substance abuse. 
Anecdotally, I was diagnosed with Generalized Anxiety Disorder and Panic Disorder when I was 16 years old. This seems like a pretty common occurrence for young women my age. That was my first glimpse into the world of mental health. As someone who was raised in a very conservative, Southern Baptist household, I was always taught that you could pray away sadness and anxiety. It wasn’t until I was in high school that I realized that the anxiety I felt on a daily basis was not the norm. I relate to your passion in wanting to make conversations about mental health more accessible and more normalized, especially in the school setting. No one should feel “othered” or stigmatized because of struggles with their mental health. Accurate and factual information is also important, as no one should be made to feel as if they could ‘pray it away.’
Overall, I really enjoyed reading this memoir. I enjoyed the way that the story was easy to follow, but interspersed with theories, statistics, and real-life information about mental disorders. Often, it seems like people are content to be ignorant about certain topics until it happens to them. Apathy is the norm when it comes to mental health, until an individual is personally affected by it. This memoir is a glance into the life of someone who didn’t have much of an awareness about mental health, but who used his son’s experiences as a catapult to educate himself about disorders, social stigma, and treatment. 
Your experiences, as told through this memoir, are important in many ways. It should serve as an example to readers, how you can use adversity to learn, grow and change. Mental health is something that we should all take an interest in, because it affects so many people in our everyday life. It may one day affect someone close to me. It is an important topic to be interested in, educated in, and to care about and advocate for. Voting is an essential way that we, as a society, can change the policies around mental health and mental health treatment. Being more aware of the problem is the only way that we can take necessary steps to fix it. If social structures are some of the main factors that lead to mental disorders in certain populations, the question becomes: what can we do to fix it? How can we better serve populations most prone to mental disorders? How can we break down gender norms and make space for every individual to feel comfortable to share their emotions and seek treatment? How can we better serve our unhoused population who have mental disorders? 
This class, and specifically, reading this memoir, have made me even more passionate about mental health awareness. Mental disorders can happen to anyone, at any time. Negative events, drug usage, even age can bring upon mental disorders on anyone. It is important to be knowledgeable about mental health and to be able to provide support to those we love who may be struggling with it. Additionally, I am a Criminology major and plan to work in Victim Advocacy in the future. I will be dealing with individuals with mental health issues who have been through traumatic events. Knowing about mental disorders is so useful and important for everyone in our generation and beyond. This memoir was an honest and important glimpse into your life, which was shaped and changed by your son’s journey with schizophrenia. It serves as a reminder that it could happen to anyone. It inspires readers to be more empathetic, to realize that we don’t always know what others are going through, and to advocate for mental health.

Family Dynamics in 2035
	Family dynamics in the United States have been changing throughout the past one hundred years. Beginning with the integration of women in the workforce, and most recently the rise in diverse family structures, it is quite clear that the “typical” family in the United States is shifting. There has been a steady decline in marriage rates alongside a rise in divorce rates. While this can partially be attributed to women gaining the right to divorce their husbands without fear of repercussions, there are many other factors, such as economic pressures, cultural values, and social media’s influence. In addition, gender roles continue to shift and are a controversial topic of conversation. Many believe that all marriages and/or relationships should be egalitarian, while others believe that traditional gender roles should be adhered to. This paper will discuss the ways in which family dynamics have shifted in the United States, as well as examine what the “typical” American family could look like in the year 2035. 
	Throughout the past one hundred years, marriage and partnership trends have begun to change and fluctuate. As mentioned, the decline in marriage rates has been a topic of conversation. Many wonder why exactly there is a decline. The marriage rate decline is due to a multitude of factors. Firstly, the cost of living has gotten so expensive that many couples choose to avoid a long-term commitment. Secondly, it is now far more normalized for a woman to value her education and career over getting married and having children. This is mainly because women no longer have to rely on a man to support them financially. Due to this, women are choosing not to get married and instead focus on their education and career. Thirdly, because the divorce rates are so high, it discourages couples from getting married in the first place. Lastly, today, cohabitation is far less stigmatized than it has been in the past. Therefore, getting married may feel “pointless.”
	Parenting and household structures have begun to see a shift as well. Women are no longer forced to stay in unhealthy relationships, which has resulted in an increase in single-parent households and co-parenting. Similarly, blended families have also become more normalized. As new styles of parenting come about, so do transformations of gender roles and work-life balance. With the steady increase in technology, new and innovative ways to care give are offered. For example, online homeschooling, AI, and digital monitoring (i.e., parental control apps, location tracking, baby monitors, etc). There has been a steady rise of women in the workforce, and this is a result of many factors. One being that fathers are being held more accountable than ever before. Therefore, it is becoming normalized to be a stay-at-home father while the mother is the breadwinner. Another factor is online job opportunities. Even if a mother desires to be a stay-at-home mom, she now has the freedom to work from home (and vice versa for stay-at-home dads). Essentially, the egalitarian lifestyle has developed into a feasible option for many households; however, it can show itself in more ways than one.  
	Many cultural and economic factors influence a family dynamic. These can be race, class, economic pressures, and the reliance on extended family and community support, just to name a few. The economic pressures that a family is placed under play a vital role in the overall family dynamic. In the United States, housing, healthcare, and childcare costs are pretty much unfeasible for the vast majority of families. This commonly results in families relying on extended family for financial support. This could be living with them, asking them to watch the children, or even helping pay for groceries, gas, doctors’ bills, etc. Thus, leading to changes in the definition of “family.” While the “typical” American family may seem like a married couple living with their children, that is simply a common stereotype. As mentioned, many couples never marry, have children together, and cohabitate. Other families may live in a multigenerational household consisting of immediate family (husband, wife, and children) alongside grandparents, aunts, uncles, and cousins. As mentioned by Andrew Cherlin, marriage has gone through an era of deinstitutionalization, accompanied by the normalization of same-sex unions as well as cohabitation. Thus, leading to the era in which America is currently experiencing. “That marriage has undergone a process of deinstitutionalization—a weakening of the social norms that define partner’ behavior—over the past few decades. Examples are presented involving the increasing number and complexity of cohabiting unions and the emergence of same-sex marriage.” (Cherlin 848).
When discussing diverse family dynamics, LGBTQ families and their inclusion into modern spaces are a hot topic. Now more than ever before, LGBTQ couples and families are being provided greater visibility when it comes to family norms. For many years, it was an extremely taboo topic that caused great controversy. While the controversy has not necessarily ended, LGBTQ individuals, couples, and families are able to integrate themselves into spaces without the fear of legal repercussions. There continue to be people who are against this; however, there is an undeniable amount of social acceptance that accompanies the legal protections. In addition, LGBTQ couples are provided with more pathways to parenthood than previous generations. Although they cannot conceive naturally, adoption and surrogacy are options that are no longer restricted by means of public policies that were inherently and clearly discriminatory. 
	As mentioned previously, technology has made a significant impact on family life. Not only does it aid parents in everyday tasks and help them monitor their children’s safety, but it also provides a space for virtual family gatherings (Zoom), communication through apps (groups on Facebook), as well as smart home tech. This is something that seems to have taken flight during the COVID-19 pandemic and has since integrated itself into the everyday life of a person and their family. Just twenty years ago, the idea of video-chatting seemed foreign. Nowadays, it is just another way of easy communication with one’s family, no matter how far apart they may be. 
	The “typical” family in 2035 is on track to look far more diverse when compared to a family fifty years ago, or even today. While I do not foresee an extreme change in just ten years, there seems to be a great possibility of a continuing shift in priorities when it comes to marriage and having a family. By 2035, the “typical” American family will, on average, lean towards the egalitarian model. The traditional nuclear model will continue to fade with an increase in single parents, co-parenting, cohabitation among partners, blended families, multigenerational households, and LGBTQ families. The nuclear model will not be obsolete but will exist alongside a much more diverse range of family models. Furthermore, with an increase in opportunities for women, the marriage rates will continue to decline. With women no longer having to marry in order to live comfortably, they may feel as if marriage and a family would hold them back from achieving their long-term goals.  
	In conclusion, the “typical” family in the United States has changed significantly throughout the past one hundred years and is only continuing to evolve. While family is a concept that most strive to have, the ways in which it is created are ever-changing. Women’s integration into the workforce has caused a decline in marriage rates simply because women no longer must rely on men. Since then, cohabitation, single parenting, and co-parenting after divorce have become far more normalized. With these family dynamics becoming less taboo, individuals and couples have been more inclined to simply go against historic social norms when it comes to starting a family. Furthermore, the concept of LGBTQ families is no longer criminalized and/or prohibited by law. With this has come opportunities for these couples to become parents through adoption and surrogacy. While many American citizens look down upon and judge those who do not subscribe to the nuclear family model, it is no secret that other family models are becoming more prominent. This is an increase that will continue to happen within the next ten years. By 2035, the “typical” American family will be continuing to shift and strive for more egalitarian models alongside a growing acceptance of diversity, technology, and flexible familial roles within the household that aim for connection and equal responsibility. This change not only reflects a shift in social structure but also an important cultural shift in America.

A Boy Broken by Douglas J. Engelman - Mid-Term Reflection
What does it mean to keep hope in the face of relentless despair? A Boy Broken reveals this through a father’s journey and sociological perspective of the trials, rewards, and tribulations of his son’s life with schizophrenia. The stigma of mental illness is a long lasting, penetrating topic that can inhibit one’s recovery and fall on the family of the people suffering. Most of the time the perspective of the family is not thought of but from personal experiences, I too know how it feels to live this reality. Some people may make mistakes on this hard course of the unknown through loss, grief, caregiving, and tough love; this story does provoke deep emotions, especially to me, as I was not always prepared in these situations. The mental health of all family’s needs to be acknowledged and made aware of helpful ways to use their experiences for the better and to help others in society diminish the stigma. 
The story starts with the end, the shock of coming back to reality, the narrow acceptance of a father hearing of the death of his son, Doug. In the words of Engelman, “...is now just a body…I imagine it cold, broken, and lifeless on a stainless-steel table in the darkness of the hospital morgue.”. But let's start with the beginning of this journey. In April 1991, 7 years before the death of his son the events began, Doug was on his sister Melissa’s porch repeating “why do they have to die?” This wasn’t normal for Doug and scared his sister. She didn’t know what to do, she had never experienced anything like this, she called the authorities, Officer Thomas. Officer Thomas alluded that Doug may be schizophrenic, their uncle Harry had been diagnosed in his 20’s, this could be true. Of course, hearing this as a parent and seeing your child in dirty clothes, preoccupied, and having a psychotic break you don’t want to believe it. Doug explained to his father that there are two people who were “always with him”, a guy named Dave who taunts him about being gay, and a girl named Wendy. This reminds me of when I first began seeing the signs that my mother had bipolar disorder II, I was just nearing my last years of high school, I had never seen any other signs or even known about the illness. I experienced lots of emotions when I found out she was suffering, and I was really the only main one there for her, I didn’t know what would come. I remember I had to either involuntarily commit her, or there would be worse consequences in the justice system, for the first time at just 16 years old. I heard the cop in the background talking bad about my mother and how he knew her in the past, displaying the same awful stigma that most law enforcement leads with. When really, he didn’t know her, what she was going through, or anything of the sort for that matter. Another moment when we began arguing a lot, I felt like it was because she wasn’t herself, but she told me “I’m the same, I have always been this way”; this made me come to the realization that I too was making her into the disorder herself and not seeing who she really is. “I can’t see her…but I believe you.”, people struggling with mental illness bring us into their chaotic world, and what it’s like but the major thing they need is someone that is going to listen and be there for them. We feel like we know this person so well, and hope that it was all just temporary. My experience as a child with a parent with a mental disorder may differ but it is also all in the same. Doug confided in his father by telling him of the diagnosis, at the McDonalds, an important moment and it brings back feelings of their past, divorce, childhood; Doug being left repeatedly by his father during his young, estranged relationship with Bobbie, Doug's mother, until now where his father had to silently promise to never leave him again, to commit. I wish the conversation could have been as open and honest, in my experience but it wasn't. It hit me like a truck, just as it does for lots of families in society, especially because I have a little brother that was too young to understand, and I had no idea how to explain it to him. I bottled all my emotions in, and I didn't want to talk to anyone, no one understood, and I was going through my own battle during all of this all alone, but she is my mom. Although I have experienced all these feelings and instances of this book, it still helped me, and I know it helps others. 
Now what? That’s the question everyone is left with. People with mental disorders “most likely lack insight into the existence of the illness and may even reject the idea of a cure.” This all plays into stigma, society sees people as socially deviant or exhibiting behavior out of the norm of their culture, stereotypes, and values. “Stigma is a “socially constructed” determination of disgrace and disapproval that can lead to profound disadvantages by those bearing the stigma.” A theory apart included in stigma is the symbolic interactionist theory, which explains that “the meaning of actions and social objects are not inherent in those objects but rather, are formed through interpretation and definition in social interaction”. There are numerous different views that can describe stigma, Georges Herbert views stigma as society norms providing the framework for his own actions. Charles Horton Cooley explains that they come to see themselves as others see us. And Lemert believes that a person sees themselves as deviant, that society has created by making ‘rules’. Again, stigma can be a barrier to recovery from mental illness, creating public and self-stigma. When a person is labeled as a mental illness it triggers negative stereotypes like fear and danger, when they really aren't. This can lead to changes in one's identity, some even say “it was how he was raised”. Altered family relationships are created from stigma; it provides a negative social framework where family has to reorganize their day-to-day routines. They must help cope with the idea that their family members will no longer be seen as acceptable in society, they feel the need to change them. “Burden falls on the family, both become the object of stigma, strained and distant relationships.” Doug’s father even hid him from his neighbors, society, everywhere, and everything to hide the fear and reality of telling the truth. He started creating false stories about what he wished Doug and Melissa’s life was really like, he hid them because of their mental illness and because of what he thought it would reflect on him, his family, and his parenting. Living with a mental illness and seeking counseling is stigmatized, the fear of rejection from many from pursuing opportunities and dreams prohibits them. There was shame and denial, both his children had a mental disorder, even though Doug was doing good he still wanted to hide the mental illness. He didn’t start sharing the real Doug until it was too late. Doug was in and out of group homes, mental facilities, therapy, apartments, it was a lot for his father and family. I feel it was probably hard on Melissa also because most of the attention was on Doug when she was going through her own mental situations. 
When a parent or child experiences a loved one being diagnosed with a mental illness, there is a sense of loss, it seems like the person is different, but still there. There are events out of the norm that we are unprepared for, and they believe they could have prevented it in some way in this long process of grief. “Unlike death, there is no “object” to mourn”, they are still there with them, but the person is unrecognizable, or even unlikable but the family has to commit to care and support. Therapists even have a tough time addressing the grief of family members. Grief started when Doug told his father about his diagnoses as they sat at the McDonalds. “My little boy, now a broken man, was a stranger, my son was gone.” Grief includes 1. Denial, 2. Anger, Doug was angry at himself as a parent, angry at God, and angry at Doug for the substances he may have used before this. 3. Bargaining, Doug’s father thought if Doug would just do what the doctors told him, he could be a part of the tiny fraction of survivors. “But this is what grief like ours does. It resists acceptance. It allows anger to consume love. And it allies hope to obscure reality.” 4. Depression, there is loss of hope that manifests, this is the quiet stage, last there is 5. Acceptance, understanding the reality of what everyone is really going through, a productive and joyful life is possible and there is potential for more positive outcomes and relationships. When you are a close family member of one with a mental illness, you can become a caregiver. Doug's father never saw it as caregiving, and neither do I with my mom, but that’s what it is. My mom takes care of herself for the most part, but there are times when this is needed. “Overall, caregivers describe feelings of isolation, financial difficulties, relationship problems, and physical complaints related to their caregiving roles.” There is lots of investment, time and energy that goes into caregiving and can even offer a sense of purpose. But like most we are often scared and anxious of what could happen when we are not there. Families that don’t have it so well and lack certain resources experience even greater stressors, discrimination, and economic insecurity. Doug went to Loyola mental facility where they prevented family interaction, he then transferred to Madden and stayed in a group home for 6 months, this was a good thing for Doug, the meds were helping push the images away, although they were still there. I have seen my mom go through many health evaluations until they settled on Latuda. The only thing about this medicine is that she's been taking it for over 10 years and if it gets out of her system, she will most likely have a manic episode. Family members don’t know the direct stress of people suffering, what is going on in their head. We are there for the evaluations, the therapy, the ups and the downs, and losing everything and starting all over again. Again, and again, but there are good parts and good can come out of it. There are downs but the ups are so much greater that they pull us out of this rut into something much better, my faith in God has helped realize we cannot control these situations, and we cannot change the person, but we can give them grace, learn their triggers, and not challenge them when they are in need.
 But sometimes they need a little tough love, Doug was allowed a weekly allowance and received disability that his father managed most of the time. When Doug was at the group home, he was having some challenges and often stated that his money was being stolen. He even tried to buy a dime bag of marijuana but got conned out of his money. Doug had to learn some responsibility. His father was upset with him that he was smoking on his meds and wanted to go off. But he gave Doug grace, it couldn't have been amazing for Doug, “Do you have any idea how shitty life is here? Nothing to do. No real friends. This tough love helps strengthen their relationship. But then Doug showed up out of the blue one night, saying he couldn't go back to the group home, and he wanted to leave because there were guys that “were going to kill him” because they thought he was gay. Doug’s father said he could not stay there, this made him upset, but he knew it was for the best. Until Doug didn’t show up to the group home and went missing for three weeks. I know that during the manic episodes with my mom, they didn’t occur frequently, but they did last a little time. Often, I would go without talking to her and had to stop by her house to check on her. One thing she thought was that all the electronics were bad, she was being tracked. During these times, I was really the only one my mom would trust, until I wasn’t. It saddened me when she would see me as the enemy or think that things were happening that weren't. But I had to learn the right approach, arguing with her and not accepting was not going to help. Things were said that I think about on the regular, I wondered did she mean these things, there was no way she didn't know she was saying. Dealing with these bouts changed me, for the better and for the worse sadly. Sometimes I would have no idea where my mom was, I would have to look for her, who was going to be there for her. All while I was trying to establish my life and finish college.  Her childhood was very tough, and her siblings were not close, their mother and father also suffered from their own mental illness. My mom is also the only child that helps my grandmother with her mental disorder. Doug's father searched for him high and low until he received a call from Doug at a homeless shelter, ah the relief to hear their voice, to know that they are okay. Doug's father cherished the late-night ride back through the city. Yeah, you're probably pissed, but they are okay. 
Through Doug's journey on the streets, he did pretty well, it had changed him for the better, but he learned that he was very fortunate to have help from Madden and security at the group home. Doug decided to get an apartment with another resident and become more independent. Then Doug decided to move back with his mom in Pittsburg, staying in his programs of course. But his mom was battling her own mental health issue, so he tried to move in with his sister and work at an art studio, he had frequent run-ins with the Dermont police. He moved from Dermont to Mercy behavioral health facility, where he met his therapist Saint Julie. Saint Julie understood Doug in a different way no one else had and Doug trusted her, this would be different. “Doug began to show indications of introspection and mature thought that he had never been able to express before his therapy with Julie". Doug had moved back to Pittsburg and became more open in social interactions with women. “Doug has gained greater insight into his disease; he developed greater understanding of the influence drugs had on his mental health and was able to remain abstinent.” Doug found a woman he really liked; with more confidence she liked him for him. She didn’t even realize he had mental illness, they had a true connection, and this was great for Doug. Doug's father was so happy for Doug and Doug knew he was doing great; things were on the up and up. Until Doug passed away on December 19, 1998. Dougs father went back to see Doug's apartment after the funeral in Cary. He thought it would be a mess, disorganized, and unclean. But instead, it was organized, clean and he even had a Christmas tree with a present from his dad and presents for his little siblings. He was taking care of himself, and he was happy, his dad was happy. “This would be his legacy; this was proof that this once broken young man was putting the pieces of his life back together. I have recalled that visit, viewing my son's life through his habitat, hundreds of times. It has helped me so often to think about how he had grown, about my journey with him, and the person that he had become through his disease and recovery.” Today, my mom is doing great, she is still here improving her life for the better, in a good area. I can say that seeing our family members with mental illness do good and better is the best thing, we were a part of the journey. It was long, it was hard, there were tears and smiles, but we made it. Every day we continue to make it and keep going. This book made me cry, smile, and relive trauma from my past experiences. I wish this book was here for me at that time, but it has done its job in helping me, one person, and I hope it continues to help everyone else in society.

Mid-Term Paper: American Families in 2035
	Recently, society has seen a shift in marriages or long-term relationships, and who the breadwinner is and who does the household chores. In the past, men were primarily the breadwinners, while women were housewives and would cook, clean, and care for the house. This dynamic has shifted going into the 21st century, and more women have entered the workforce. Some men have also shifted to stay-at-home dads, but the question of relationship equality still exists. Many old norms and traditions are still held up today, even though society is pushing towards an egalitarian relationship model. Many couples are also refraining from getting married or having kids. With all of these factors up in the air, it leaves many possibilities for a relationship to lean towards in the future. While these were some bigger factors, some smaller, seemingly insignificant influences also have a big impact. 
	Currently, we live in a society that is rapidly developing newer and more advanced models of technology. Technology is growing faster than society can keep up with, and it impacts society on large and small scales. Whether or not we realize it, technology has an extreme impact on families and their dynamics. I see this personally at my job every day. I work as a server in a local restaurant, and oftentimes when I go to greet a table, everyone at the table is on their phones. I’m not judging by any means. I’m on my phone more than I like, but throughout the entire dining experience, everyone is on their phones rather than talking. I believe that this is negatively affecting the family dynamic, and unless it is addressed, it may continue to harm families and cause many issues in the years to come. This is not just my opinion; sociological researchers are also concerned about this issue. Lee et al. (2022) examined how parental efficacy and methods, along with mobile device usage in children, negatively impact a child’s relationship with technology and the family dynamic. The researchers' findings indicated that overconsumption and reliance on mobile devices are more likely to lead to negative outcomes. They mentioned that children holding mobile devices constantly will interfere with their daily lives, thus affecting their relationships and daily lives (Lee et al., 2022).  This has many implications for how families may look and operate in 2035. 
Small things can have big implications on family dynamics, as seen with mobile devices. Things like quality time are extremely important to build strong and deep connections. Not having deep connections in relationships can lead to other tough situations, like Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs). One ACE that is most commonly seen in families is substance use and abuse. According to Jabbari (2023), substance use and abuse can be affected by unhealthy family dynamics, especially in adolescents. Sometimes adolescents are looking for a way to escape or to regain a sense of control over their lives, which often manifests in them sneaking out or using substances. Jabbari (2023) also suggests that those in stressful family situations tend to gravitate towards unhealthy coping mechanisms, which impacts their health. Unhealthy family dynamics impact everyone in the family individually, as well as the whole unit. 
	So how does all of this play into the future dynamics of American families in 2035? There are a couple of different ways that families could go. One dynamic is a detached, unemotional, power struggle dynamic. This is the worst possible case scenario. This dynamic depicts a family that is not close, spends no time together, and is constantly fighting for attention. The parents would be fighting for equality in breadwinning, which would leave no room for quality time for their children. These children would grow up without a strong foundation, and if their parents suddenly tried to discipline them, then it would create an unhealthy dynamic. This dynamic would create the most strife and distance within the family. 
	Another dynamic would be a semi-balanced family dynamic. This dynamic would still have some strife and cause some issues between the parents themselves and the parents and children. In this dynamic, there is more of a balance with breadwinning and less competing. Both parents may work or only one, but they are working together to be financially stable. If only one person is working, it may cause some issues with providing for the family and the splitting of household chores. This may also cause strife with their children, especially if one parent is more present than the other. Even with some of the strife, this would be more optimal than the example in the previous paragraph. 
	The last dynamic depicts the most perfect dynamic in the ever-changing society that we live in. This would mean that no matter what each parent is doing, whether they are both at work or just one, they are both equally contributing to housework and taking care of their family. Their relationships with their children would be close and trusting. There would be no unhealthy dynamics like substance abuse or abuse. This would be the most optimal, but this seems to be harder to reach. 
In conclusion, many factors impact a family’s dynamic. There are large-scale and small-scale factors. All of these factors combined can have a multitude of effects. Ultimately, there is no way to predict a “typical American family in 2035.” Society changes so much in ten years, and it’s difficult to predict everything. Technology is changing constantly, and social media is impacting how we view society and how we should handle family dynamics. Families can be complicated, but I’m hoping that the last scenario is what we are heading towards as a society.

The Future of Applying Ideological Equality in America
	Over the course of the past century America has shifted from a relatively homogeneous culture placing priority on assimilation and the nuclear family to a more diverse society defined by stratified social identities. Towards the end of the civil rights movement the codified laws which would be created in the name of forcing an end to segregation would see many positive outcomes but in practice some mandates have often fallen short due to inconsistent enforcement and uneven social integration. To contrast, the most homogeneous societies of the world are also the ones with the best success of welfare implementation, as social consensus and shared norms can simplify policy coordination. In the United States, however, the ongoing struggle to balance cultural diversity with cohesive national identity has placed increased pressure on traditional family structures. This family structure shift stems from the struggles of maintaining a non-homogenous national identity and prospects of the shape this could take tend to form around two schools of thought.
	Firstly, the once normative traditional American family with a husband, wife, and kids has now become the counterculture and can be predicted to see a return due to the weakness of maintaining collective values in an increasingly diverse society. Most trends fluctuate so seeing a return to form based on strong family bonds free of ambiguity is a viable option. Many today believe rapid social changes have progressed too forcibly due to the application of political agendas on social thought instead of organic cultural evolution. Current debates over family values, gender roles, and cultural identity have been often too politicized. This changes what would otherwise be normative social adaptations into an ideological battleground. This politicization risks obscuring genuine discussions about how best to gauge a balance between equality, stability, and personal freedom within modern family life.
The crux of the issue can be understood when looking at the codified laws being proposed to combat inequality in the workplace and household. The ultimate logic for dictating a replacement of social norms is not clearly defined in many instances allowing for perpetual violations of the ultimate cause being fought for. This issue is not new as various civil rights laws like the Title 7 of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Equal Pay Act of 1963 suffer from the same issue of legal ambiguity. One good example of modern equality legislation passed in the UK in recent years. Laws like the Equality Act of 2010 (UK) often leave ambiguous explanations on how it intends to change social norms. The ultimate change achieved by these types of legislation are inherently weak because even though it defines new standards to meet, things like failing to define sexual orientation clearly end up not enshrining the social leap it was intended to. This applies to the US because there was intent on implementing an adapted version which never came to fruition. 
The sociological thinker Durkheim comes to mind when defining the problems of practicing ambiguous policies. To quote Sociology of Law by Milovanovic on Durkheim social philosophy, he states “Durkheim assumes that society, left to itself, will evolve from the traditional to the complex form,” existing in “a state of equilibrium.” However, “when these adjustments do not take place,” he notes, “a state Durkheim referred to as anomie” emerges, an idea “many criminologists embed or assume in their explanation of crime.” (Milovanovic 2022, p.67) This state of anomie (normlessness) can be seen much more vividly than ever before, perhaps resulting in accepted application of normlessness as the norm. Something as simple as the man paying on the first date or asking another on a date is being actively torn down making what was already a difficult hurdle for people to make now being thrown into question; a socially accepted procedure for centuries. This state of anomie, or normlessness, according to Durkheim’s philosophy, is also linked to suicide. In a time when the application of equitable laws is at an all-time high, this may correlate with rising male suicide rates from 18.1 per 100,000 in 1968 to 22.8 per 100,000 in 2023, an increase of 26% (National Institute of Mental Health) potentially reflecting a displacement of their societal roles.
To understand the place that counter-traditional relational ideologies will take in the coming years you need to first break down the aspects these groups use to define themselves. The future of gay couples in America is undoubtedly an important one and many social thinkers believe these social advancements are being normalized much like racial integration once was. There are many debates within LGBTQ+ movements about how internal representation and behavior have influenced public perceptions, sometimes hindering support. There is no better way to tear down a movement than to evoke societal reactions to perceived displays of misconduct. The civil rights activists did a very good job at showing how strongly spoken they were to the public and everything from the way they dressed to the way they organized and conducted themselves saw them winning social acceptance, changing predominant beliefs. Homosexuality being sexual in nature has seen problems of acceptance due to displays of social misconduct and demands of image reorientation are needed in order to spark lasting transformative change. Recognizing how image and perception influence public acceptance is essential as these factors directly impact whether policies aimed at family equality achieve genuine integration or remain symbolically progressive.
Along the more contemporary lines of reform, if Europe is to be used as a model for America in the coming years there are plenty of positive and negative takeaways to understand before new laws become formalized. Positive takeaways include laws like Norway's Paid Parental Leave and “Use-It-or-Lose-It” quotas which sees all parents being entitled to paid leave even reserving a portion for fathers. This is a good example because not only does it shift workplace norms but it also helps the parents fulfil their family duties at home. One other example would be Germany's Anti-Discrimination Act (Allgemeines Gleichbehandlungsgesetz, AGG) which nets some benefits like providing a clear legal framework for victims of workplace discriminatory practices and a focus on encouraging proactive HR policies. The categorizations within this remedy based approach helps reduce confusion in interpretation allowing for clear paths for enforcement. 
Regarding examples not to follow France’s Gender Parity in Politics Law (2000) and EU’s Directive on Work-Life Balance (2019) provide a good contrast. With France’s law it explains a requirement for political parties to present 50% female, 50% male candidate nomination. Results here are thoroughly superficial as the issue of political representation among women in France, even though statistically improved, still lacks a qualitative effect with women being placed in local non-competitive districts for party compliance purposes. The EU directive on work life balance sees a different set of issues. It is designed to encourage flexible working arrangements and parental leave across EU states but because it is another EU law designed to be applied in countries with completely different internal interests application and enforcement suffer putting into question the integrity of the law’s legitimization. The United States can learn from this aspect especially in a time where federal legal precedent is used to apply to states which fail to share social values of other states. Laws are always best applied at the state level first and foremost because they’re more likely to reflect the communities interests. When it comes to family representation nothing could be farther away than a federal mandate.
The failure of social legislation to alleviate pressures on families forces new generations to adapt resulting in individualized social nets to form at an advanced rate. While this can be economically beneficial by eliminating financial dependence on others, phenomena like the single mother epidemic and the rise of less conventional blended families present their own instabilities. It would be a disservice of governance to supplement these situations without first addressing the systemic roots of unideal living situations. True reform requires legislation that strengthens the social foundations of family life. This can be achieved by focussing on wage inequality, affordable childcare, and accessible housing (the Blackrock problem) rather than policies that merely treat the symptoms of deeper structural imbalance. Without this shift, future generations will continue to bear the private costs of public inaction, mistaking adaptation for progress. Social change is slow so in the year 2035 the differences from 2025 are going to be negligible even if federal mandates are created today the process of trickling into the social consciousness will not be completed.

If one parent stays at home it is most likely assumed to be the mom, which can come with its own issues of mom doing more labor at home and feeling overworked and that labor not being recognized, and if it is the father at home, there is a huge stigma that they only sit around and do not care properly for their child. If they both choose to work, there could be the issue of the mom having to deal with the “second shift.” Meaning she must come home from her nine to five job and then come do household chores and childcare etc. on her own. (Hochschild & Machung, 1989) Which causes an imbalance of how much each parent contributes to the home. If they both decide they want to try and do both in equal measure, they often will find that they are always losing out on either free time at home catching up on things or find that they must be absent from work often. It is hard to find a balance between doing both care and working.  (Hochschild & Machung, 1989)

This brings back our original question based on what is seen now: what might the typical family in 2035 look like? Based on what has been seen It is safe to say that our typical family structure still will likely look like a nuclear one. It is safe to try and predict that as we see that other family structures are struggling to become made or are thought of as normative. Two parents and their children are likely still going to be the normative family, if they choose to have any. However, it may not hold the traditional gender roles or traditional differential sex parent make up.  I think we are growing more acceptive of LGBTQ parents having children and still seeing that as a family. However, things such as polyamorous families and couples, kinship and village networks, etc. are still not seen as proper families or the norm. It is likely there will be a push towards trying to provide and be equally involved in relationships, the household, and parenting. What that looks like will likely be different for each family like how it does now. The way that this will likely be done is by investing greater effort into finding balance within work and personal life and time as we are seeing a trend now of that. 


In conclusion, based on the trends we are seeing now, even though it may be hard to make airtight predictions due to different influences and how fast we can see trends ebb and flow based on them, it is safe to assume within the next ten years we can expect more continued growth and change within these different areas. Particularly in the areas of what and who we consider a family, gender roles in marriage and families, childcare, how parents respond to the work force, etc. These changes, although they may not be big, will hopefully be continuing a track of growth that we are seeing and not a regression of where trends are now.

	Michael Joseph Sandel is a very accomplished and acclaimed American political philosopher and professor at Harvard University. Michael Joseph Sandel is very well known for his internationally bestselling book called “Justice: What’s the Right Thing to Do?” Throughout this book, Michael Joseph Sandel expands on his ideologies about morals, ethics, laws, and politics. He connects real-world events to different theories of justice, like utilitarianism and libertarianism, as well as different philosophers' ideas, such as Kant, Aristotle, and Rawls. Michael Joseph Sandel's book serves as a clear, engaging, and well-written piece of literature that challenges readers to reflect on their own beliefs and moral compasses. Michael Sandel's book “Justice: What’s the Right Thing to Do” also laid the foundation for a lifelong career dedicated to involving the public in moral, ethical, and civil discussions. 
	In Michael Joseph Sandel’s book “Justice: What’s the Right Thing to Do?”, he states that there are three approaches to justice. A society distributes different things we prize, including income and wealth, duties and responsibilities, powers and opportunities, and offices and honors. A society that is just distributes these things fairly and equitably, giving each individual his or her due. Michael Sandel states, however, “The hard questions begin when we ask what people are due, and why” (pg. 17). The first idea of justice is maximizing welfare. Maximizing welfare is centered around the ideas of promoting prosperity, improving our standard of living, and producing the overall greatest good for a society. Michael Sandel further explains this ideology by connecting it to the philosophical approach of utilitarianism. Utilitarianism is a moral theory that emphasizes the importance of the greater good. If an action promotes the greatest happiness and well-being for the greatest number of people, then it is right. Individuals who follow the utilitarianism approach often evaluate their actions by asking themselves Does it improve the overall quality of life and welfare? While utilitarianism sounds simple enough, it also has its negatives that come along with it. Utilitarianism can overlook individual rights and justify acts of injustice as long as they result in a greater good for a majority of people. While I do personally think that utilitarianism can be an effective tool for maximizing happiness and welfare, I do think it has a few drawbacks that raise some ethical and moral concerns. 
	The second approach links justice to freedom. In this section of Michael Joseph Sandel's book, he explains that a wide range of theories emphasize respect for individual rights and decisions. Sandel states that “The idea that justice means respecting freedom and individual rights is at least as familiar in contemporary politics as the utilitarian idea of maximizing welfare.” For example, the U.S. Bill of Rights sets out certain liberties—including rights to freedom of speech and religious liberty—that even majorities may not violate. And around the world, the idea that justice means respecting certain universal human rights is increasingly embraced (in theory, if not always in practice). (pg. 19). This approach is broad and uses both libertarian and egalitarian views. On one side, Sandel states that libertarians argue “that justice consists in respecting and upholding the voluntary choices made by consenting adults” (pg. 19), while egalitarians argue that “unfettered markets are neither just nor free. In their view, justice requires policies that remedy social and economic disadvantages and give everyone a fair chance at success” (pg. 19). Both the libertarian and egalitarian arguments linking justice to freedom have strong points as well as limitations. I personally think that I agree more with the egalitarian argument. I think that in order for everyone to truly be free, we need to address the more deeply rooted structural inequalities and biases, and social injustices that are among us. I believe that justice is truly served when everyone has equal access to different opportunities and chances at success. 
	In the third approach, Michael Joseph Sandel connects justice to virtue and the good life. This approach highlights the idea that justice isn’t only about the outcomes but also about promoting certain moral values and ethics within a society. Sandel goes on to explain that different moral and religious ideologies have shaped political movements and arguments for decades. One example of this is Martin Luther King Jr., who drew his visions and ideas of what justice looks like from different moral and religious perspectives. The approach that connects justice to virtue and the good life shows us that debates and different opinions about what justice is are often intertwined with the different values a society chooses to uphold. 
	All three of Michael Joseph Sandel's approaches to justice—maximizing welfare, linking justice to freedom, and connecting justice to virtue—show just how complex it is to determine what justice really is and what it looks like. Sandals' explanations of the three approaches to justice really make me think about the deeper values and individual morals that shape our choices and decisions. Everyone has a different perspective on what justice should look like, and these different approaches encourage us to think about what justice is to us. Sandel provides us with an example of how our moral reasoning leads us to the decisions we make. In the example of The Runaway Trolley, Sandel states that “Suppose you are the driver of a trolley car hurtling down the track at sixty miles an hour. Up ahead, you see five workers standing on the track, tools in hand. You try to stop, but you can’t. The brakes don’t work. Suddenly, you notice a side track off to the right. There is a worker on that track, too, but only one. You realize that you can turn the trolley car onto the side track, killing the one worker but sparing the five. Now consider another version where you are an onlooker. The trolley is about to crash into the five workers. You feel helpless to avert this disaster—until you notice, standing next to you on the bridge, a very heavy man. You could push him off the bridge, onto the track, into the path of the oncoming trolley. He would die, but the five workers would be saved” (pg. 20). I found the example of the runaway trolley to be very interesting because it truly does raise a moral and ethical puzzle. Individuals will have different ideas on what choice is correct, and this example goes to show that everyone has different moral principles, dilemmas, and perspectives on what is considered right and wrong. 
	Michael Joseph Sandel shows us how different individuals face different moral dilemmas, which further reveal the way people view topics “about right and wrong, justice and injustice. Some people favor abortion rights, and others consider abortion to be murder. Some believe fairness requires taxing the rich to help the poor, while others believe it is unfair to tax away money people have earned through their own efforts. Some defend affirmative action in college admissions as a way of righting past wrongs, whereas others consider it an unfair form of reverse discrimination against people who deserve admission on their merits. Some people reject the torture of terror suspects as a moral abomination unworthy of a free society, while others defend it as a last resort to prevent a terrorist attack” (pg. 27). While it may seem like our moral convictions are fixed by our upbringing or faith, I believe that our morals can change. Throughout our lifetimes, we are faced with different situations that challenge our personal principles and morals. Sandel states that in order for justice to be discovered, different debates, dialogues, and ideologies must be had, and sometimes our minds can be changed. Throughout the book, Sandel brings up the different perspectives of Aristotle, Immanuel Kant, John Stuart Mill, and John Rawls to encourage us to further examine our own morals and to figure out why we think the way we do. 
	Immanuel Kant (1724-1804) offers us one of the most powerful accounts of duties and rights. Kant’s account depends on the ideology that we are rational beings worthy of dignity and respect. Kant’s groundwork relates to the question of “What is the supreme principle of morality?” and in the course of answering that question, it addresses another hugely important one: “What is freedom?” (pg. 104). Kant's opinion on freedom challenges our understanding of morality because he believes that true freedom is acting according to the principles we have given ourselves. Kant rejects utilitarianism because he believes that it leaves rights vulnerable, and just because something benefits the majority doesn't make it morally right. Kant also believes that every individual deserves respect because they are rational beings capable of reason and making choices. Kant also believes that freedom is our obedience to impulses that we don’t get to choose. To act freely is to act autonomously according to the moral laws we give ourselves. I do personally have some critiques of Kant’s philosophy. I believe that his ideology is almost too rigid at times. Kant believes that moral rules are absolute, especially when it comes to lying. I personally believe that lying is ok in some instances. One personal example of where I believe that it was ok for me to lie was when I was babysitting. The little girl and I were painting together, and she asked me if her painting she made of her and her parents was good (it was not). I obviously lied and said yes because why would you tell a little girl that her painting was not the best? I believe that in this situation, it was ok for me to lie in order to spare the little girl's feelings. While Kant would argue that all lying undermines morality, I believe that in some instances lying is ok. Morality requires flexibility, context, and empathy. 
	Sandel's book on justice provides us with different philosophical ideologies and perspectives that we can use to help us face our problems today. He compares different views on what justice is, like libertarianism and egalitarianism, and draws on different philosophical perspectives, like Immanuel Kant's. I found Kant’s perspective on morality and freedom to be quite interesting, but also too strict at times. All these different ideologies and perspectives make me really think about what justice and morality are and should look like in our daily lives.
