The Future of Families Through the Eyes of a College Student
Over the past 80 or so years, we have seen several changes in the typical family structure. What used to be common in the 40s and 50s is much different from what we see today, or is it? The traditional nuclear family has expanded and can seem somewhat unfamiliar, but when taking a closer look, it appears that society’s ideas have not ventured as far as we think. While stigmatizations have changed quite a bit, society still tends to be set in what could be considered traditional.
Marriage and Divorce Rates
The stigma surrounding divorce has subsided greatly compared to what it was before World War II. 	Sheela Kennedy and Steven Ruggles (2014) share that individuals who are forty or older tend to have higher divorce rates, especially after World War II. This can be attributed to the fact that divorce was no longer highly stigmatized, but also the legality of divorce changed significantly (Kennedy & Ruggles, 2014). We can see during this time that women were allowed to enter the workforce at a much higher rate than before. This access to jobs meant access to money, which meant that a woman could have financial freedom. Women now had access to leave their husbands and be financially stable on their own terms. 
We have seen a decline in divorce rates among women who are age twenty-five or younger (Kennedy & Ruggles, 2014). This decline can be associated with the lack of marriage in the first place. Kennedy and Ruggles (2014) mention that in 2008, over forty percent of the population was not married by the time they turned thirty. A lot of this has to do with individuals being more selective in their partners compared to the past. Couples before World War II got married to fulfill societal roles, whereas now, we see couples dating or getting married to fulfill individual goals. 
I believe that divorce rates could swing either way. In one instance, I think that religion is becoming increasingly popular again. In the event that this popularity continues to increase, we could see an increase in traditional marriages once again, with a lower divorce rate. We may also see a decrease in divorce rates because couples are simply not getting married. Cohabitation is common and is beginning to possess the same rights as couples who are married. In this instance, I think we will see that marriage becomes less important, and therefore, divorce rates would decline. In another scenario, I could see divorce rates rising. You rarely see people being stigmatized for divorce; instead, it is applauded for the fact that you are strong enough to remove yourself from whatever situation it may be. There is a lot more freedom when it comes to divorce in the fact that a woman or a man can initiate a divorce. With those ideas in mind, I can see divorce rates increasing. Honestly, there is no perfect answer for how that will change in ten years. It could be exactly what it is today, or it can change completely.
Traditional Nuclear Families: Stay away or make a comeback?
We have seen a big shift away from traditional nuclear families. Society is much more open to cohabitation, same-sex marriages, and single parents. Cohabitation has increased drastically since World War II. We are now seeing that marriages typically begin with cohabitation instead of living separately until marriage (Smock, 2000). I have noticed an increase in cohabitation among college students living with significant others. Cohabitation has become very similar to marriage, which in turn makes it “good enough” for those who aren’t quite ready for the responsibilities that come with marriage. In 2035, I believe that cohabitation will become the norm for people. I almost want to say that the number of people cohabitating will be much greater than those who are actually married.
Another nontraditional family type is same-sex couples. In 2011, only seven states in America legally allowed same-sex marriages (Chamie & Mirkin, 2011). This has since changed with the Supreme Court’s ruling in 2015 that legalized same-sex marriages in all fifty states. Previously, same-sex marriage was not only legally unavailable, but there was a great deal of stigma that came with it. Now, we see much more acceptance; however, there are certainly opposing groups that do not believe in same-sex marriage and do not believe it should be legal. I think that if we continue the path we are currently on, same-sex marriage will remain legal and most likely continue to hold similar statistics as it does now. With that being said, I still firmly believe that we will have a group of people who will continue to oppose the allowance of same-sex marriages. 
While these rates are increasing, we also see an increase in single parents, specifically single mothers. Single parents were not common prior to World War II, as families were trying to fulfill societal roles. Now, we see an increase in divorces or never-married couples because individuals are more likely to prioritize themselves. With these separation rates, it is more likely that a child will be under the care of a single parent. Mothers tend to get custody of the children, whether that be court-ordered or because the father does not put in the same effort. This, of course, can go both ways. In 1984, 25.7% of families were single-family households, accounting for one-fourth of the population (Hanson & Sporakowski, 1986). In the college age group, it is common for a teen pregnancy to occur and the mother to be the primary caregiver. Through my own experience, I have noticed that the majority of my friends who live with single parents live with their mothers. I do not see this changing a whole lot in the next ten years. We have normalized divorce, which increases the number of single-parent households. I will not say that the number of single-parent households will increase, but I do think that it will continue to stay at a similar level compared to what it is now. 
So, what will the world be like in ten years?
Overall, I think that the structure of families will continue the path that they are on now. We will continue to see divorce rates increase or plateau because of how society has normalized it. An increase in divorce rates can be a leading cause for single-parent families. I also think that we will continue to see a rise in same-sex marriages. Since it has become legal, we have seen an increase. I do think that this will continue as it becomes less stigmatized and more normalized. 
I don’t see us reverting to past traditions and normalizing marriages as something to satisfy societal roles. We have opened the gates by allowing women in the workforce and pushing towards egalitarian roles. I believe that egalitarianism will become the most popular format for families moving forward. I think certain things need to be fixed to achieve an egalitarian society, but if we continue to push, we might get there. Things like fixing the wage gap, finding better solutions to childcare, and allowing Americans to have a better work-life balance. It is very prevalent that egalitarian relationships are subjective, and the definition of egalitarianism is dependent on the couple. While we will never know what the future will bring, I predict that these could be some of the possible outcomes. Of course, we see rapid changes in history, meaning we have the potential to experience these norms changing without having any insight currently.
